<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greene Wins Sprint Double Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- For Maurice Greene, nothing changed much in  
the Prefontaine Classic, not even the strong wind, as he swept the 
sprint double for the second straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing changed much for Marion Jones and Michael Johnson either  
as they won their specialties. 
</P>
<P>
	And the 25th Prefontaine Classic Sunday again produced another  
outstanding mile, with 10 runners breaking the four-minute barrier, 
led by Kenya's Noah Ngeny. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, ranked No. 1 in the world in the 100 meters and the 1997  
world champion, won the 100 in 9.84 seconds, a time that equaled 
Canadian Donovan Bailey's world record but was negated by a wind of 
7.83 mph, well over the allowable of 4.473 for record purposes. The 
clocking has been bettered only six other times. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty minutes later, Greene won the 200 in 20.06, a time that  
would have broken the meet record of 20.15 by Johnson in 1995, if 
not for the wind. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, with slightly less wind, Greene ran even faster,  
winning the 100 in 9.79 and the 200 in 19.88. Still it was over the 
limit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this track loves me, and I love this track,'' Greene  
said. ``I love this city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene's love affair with Eugene and the University of Oregon's  
Hayward Field will continue next month at the USA Championships, 
the qualifying meet for the World Championships. He is expected to 
face Johnson in a 200 showdown. 
</P>
<P>
	As world champion in the 100, Greene does not have to qualify in  
that event. Neither does Johnson in the 400, since he also is the 
world champion. Thus, both will concentrate on the 200 for the 
national championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 200 was a little challenging,'' Greene said after his  
magnificent double that excited the crowd of 12,247. ``I was winded 
after the 100. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I'm in good enough shape where I can go back-to-back.''  
</P>
<P>
	Greene said he was not frustrated at losing his shot at records  
because of the wind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not the wind God,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, ranked No. 1 in the world in the 400 eight times, beat  
world No. 2 Mark Richardson of Britain by nearly 10 meters at 
44.51, matching his best time of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The wind was blowing hard down the backstretch, so running a  
good time today was pretty much impossible,'' said Johnson, who 
thought he was in shape to break 44 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, track and field's woman athlete of the year for the past  
two years, was competing for the first time in more than a month. 
</P>
<P>
	But she won the 200 by about nine meters in 21.81, the fastest  
time in the world this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to go through the season undefeated because I've yet to  
do that,'' said Jones, who lost only once last year, in her final 
competition of the season, in the long jump. 
</P>
<P>
	While the near-capacity crowd roared its approval for the  
sprinters, it saved its loudest cheers for the men's milers. 
</P>
<P>
	The milers went through a quarter-mile meters in 56:00, then the  
20-year-old Ngeny took the field through a 1:56.02 half-mile and 
was timed at 2:54.9 for three-quarters, before pulling away down 
the final straightway and winning at 3:52.09, fastest in the world 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's Kevin Sullivan, the former Michigan star, finished  
second at 3:53.70, and Adam Goucher, the 1999 national indoor 3,000 
champion and 1998 NCAA 5,000 winner for Colorado, was third at 
3:54.17. It was his career best and the best by an American this 
year. Americans Karl Paranya, fifth at 3:54.83, and Steve Holman, 
eighth at 3:55.13, also cracked the four-minute barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Wade, who came into the meet as the world leader in the  
110 hurdles, lowered his best time to 13.12. Reggie Torian, the 
runner-up at 13.17, also went under Wade's previous leading time of 
13.22. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17-event program produced three other 1999 American leaders.  
</P>
<P>
	Regina Jacobs, a seven-time national champion, won the women's  
1,500 meters at 4:07.90. Lance Deal, the American record-holder in 
the hammer throw, won at 261 feet, 2 inches, and Bob Kennedy, the 
American record-holder at 5,000 meters, finished third at 13:18.83, 
behind Kenya's Luke Kipkosgei (13:17.15) and Mexico's Pablo Olmedo 
(13:18.21). 
</P>
<P>
	There were two other surprises, as Lawrence Johnson, the former  
American record-holder in the pole vault, beat current 
record-holder Jeff Hartwig, 18-8 1-4 to 18-4 1-2, and Andy Bloom, 
the former NCAA shot put and discus champion from Wake Forest, beat 
1999 world leader John Godina, 220-0 to 217-8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
