<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ewing Shrugs Off Pain To Help Knicks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Patrick Ewing grabbed the last-second  
airball and cradled it in his long arms, a victory over the Indiana 
Pacers secured, another step toward the one goal that has eluded 
him -- an NBA championship -- taken. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing's knees were covered by braces and pads and his painful  
left Achilles' tendon was wrapped as well. His left shoulder was 
sore, so was his right quadriceps and he's been dealing with a 
strained rib cage muscle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think any other body part could hurt him. I don't  
think there are any left,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes after the game, Ewing's ordeal was evident. He wore an  
ice bag on his right knee and then checked a timer to see when it 
was OK to bring his submerged left leg out of a bucket of ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm all banged up,'' Ewing said after a courageous 40-minute  
performance Sunday. He scored 16 points and grabbed 10 rebounds to 
help the Knicks beat the Pacers 93-90 in the opening game of the 
Eastern Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing hit four free throws in the final minute and he also made  
a key defensive play late in the game, running out at Reggie Miller 
and causing him to hurry and miss a 3-pointer that could have given 
Indiana the lead in the final seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patrick has seen that play 200 times and he knew it was  
coming. Injury or not, his understanding of the game of basketball 
is good. It was a good hedge on his part,'' Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's satisfying, basically, to win. A lot of people have been  
doubting us. We just seem to keep fighting to do what we have to to 
stay alive,'' Ewing said following New York's sixth straight 
playoff victory, a club record. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to do it bad and when you want to do it that bad, you  
step up the best way you can and try to get it done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His teammates have marveled at the 36-year-old's ability to deal  
with pain. Nearly a week had passed since the Knicks swept the 
Atlanta Hawks in the second round and that gave him some needed 
rehab time. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can see him wince in pain and for him to come out and down  
the stretch give us what he gave us, it's unspeakable,'' Knicks 
guard Allan Houston said. 
</P>
<P>
	``For him to hit those big free throws, you can't say enough  
what he's been giving us throughout the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Kurt Thomas agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``You just to have to look at him and say he's a warrior, a  
leader,'' said Thomas, who contributed eight points, eight rebounds 
and some good defense on Pacers center Rik Smits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patrick's doing whatever it takes to get out there on the  
floor.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
