<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A street child was killed and an  
American tourist injured in a drive-by shooting in Rio's Copacabana 
district early Sunday, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan Gordon, 22, from Texas, was hit in the thigh by a stray  
bullet but was not seriously injured, said detective Paulo 
Ferreira. The gunman had aimed at the street child. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, who was being treated Sunday at a Rio hospital, was on a  
trip to Brazil as a member of the Hamilton Park Male Choir, he 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	The 16-year-old street child, whose name was unavailable, died,  
said Ferreira. The motive for the shooting was unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's oldest opposition party has voted to  
adopt a presidential primary for the July 2000 elections, following 
in the footsteps of the governing Institutional Revolutionary 
Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 6,000 delegates at a national assembly for the center-right  
National Action Party voted late Saturday to hold a national 
primary open to members and registered ``sympathizers'' of the 
party. The election was expected to be held in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The move came less than two weeks after the governing party,  
known as the PRI, voted to hold its first national primary, ending 
a tradition where the outgoing president selects the party's 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1939, the National Action Party struggled for decades  
against rigged elections and a system stacked in favor of the PRI 
until winning its first governorship in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	The party, whose main strength is among businessmen, middle  
class and religiously inclined voters, has taken advantage of 
democratic reforms in Mexico and now governs Baja California, 
Queretaro, San Luis Potosi, Jalisco, Guanajuato and Nuevo Leon. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- The center-left coalition that has ruled  
Chile since the end of Gen. Augusto Pinochet's military 
dictatorship, held a primary election on Sunday to pick its 
candidate for December's presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricardo Lagos, a moderate socialist, and Andres Zaldivar, of the  
centrist Christian Democratic party, were the candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called Coalition for Democracy, which was formed to fight  
the Pinochet regime, has won every election since civilian rule was 
restored in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The right wing opposition has already nominated its candidate:  
37-year-old economist Joaquin Lavin, mayor of the affluent Las 
Condes County in Santiago. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 6 million people were eligible to vote in Sunday's  
election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
