<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> One Race Down, One to Go for Stewart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- One race, no problem for Tony Stewart's  
quest for auto racing history. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to become the first driver to complete the Indianapolis  
500 and the Coca-Cola 600 in the same day, Stewart accomplished the 
first part of his goal with ease. He finished ninth in a day where 
several of the top racers were knocked out by crashes and engine 
blowouts. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't the easiest race, though. After starting in the eighth  
row, he had trouble with his car for much of the day, though he 
managed to stay in the top 10 for almost the entire race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good job, buddy. Thanks for hanging in there,'' crew chief  
Larry Curry said as the race ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after, Stewart sprinted for the helicopter that took him  
to the Indianapolis airport, where The Home Depot, his sponsor, had 
its private jet waiting for the 50-minute flight to North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a 50-minute flight to North Carolina, and then he's got  
another helicopter ride to Lowe's Motor Speedway. He'll start in 
the 27th spot in the Coca-Cola. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the long day, Stewart looked loose and relaxed Sunday  
morning. When he walked to his race car, his crew handed him two 
helmets and told him to pick one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eenie, meenie, minie, mo,'' Stewart said as his crew laughed.  
</P>
<P>
	After three years in the Indy Racing league, Stewart switched to  
NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit and has done better than anyone 
expected. He's had five top-10 finishes in his first 12 races, and 
his won one pole. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 28-year-old Indiana native didn't want to give up his  
chance to win at Indy. Even if it meant driving 1,100 miles in less 
than 12 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``A beautiful sunny day like this, I suppose people could figure  
out better things to do than drive 1,100 miles,'' he said. ``But 
I'm looking forward to doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Andretti was the first to do the double in 1994, but he  
crashed in the Coca-Cola 600 and didn't finish the race. Robby 
Gordon's attempt in 1997 was rained out in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart has been shuttling back and forth between Indy and  
Concord the past two weeks, and he arrived in Indianapolis late 
Saturday after two days of practice in North Carolina. He slept in 
his motor coach at the speedway, and he and fiancee Krista Dwyer 
arrived at his garage about 9:25 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	As he walked onto the track, there were loud cheers from the  
crowd. People dashed in front of him to get pictures, and several 
drivers stopped to wish him luck. 
</P>
<P>
	His father, Nelson, caught up to his son, gave him a bear hug  
and told him to have a good day. Not a problem, Stewart said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel pretty good,'' he said. ``I'm ready to get the day  
started and get this part of it over.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
