<DOCNO> APW19990530.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 20:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Astronauts Enter Space Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Still elated from their successful  
work outside, Discovery's astronauts swung open the hatches of the 
international space station tonight and floated into the chilly but 
brightly lighted outpost. 
</P>
<P>
	They were the first visitors in six months.  
</P>
<P>
	``Make yourself at home,'' radioed Mission Control.  
</P>
<P>
	Before the seven shuttle astronauts began opening the doors,  
flight controllers warned it would be 57 degrees in the first 
module, the American-made Unity. 
</P>
<P>
	``You might want to bring a sweater,'' Mission Control advised.  
</P>
<P>
	They had to pass through six hatches to get all the way in, a  
drawn-out affair that took more than two hours because of the need 
to equalize the pressure in the various compartments. Mission 
Control helped by turning on the lights ahead of them. 
</P>
<P>
	American Tamara Jernigan and Russian Valery Tokarev led the way.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are absolutely delighted to be aboard,'' Jernigan said.  
</P>
<P>
	Discovery's astronauts will spend the next three days making  
repairs and deliveries to the 240-mile-high station, vacant since 
another shuttle crew joined the first two components in orbit back 
in December. The work is bigger and far more tedious than what they 
did earlier Sunday during the second-longest spacewalk ever -- 
rigging cranes and other tools to the exterior. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the jobs awaiting them inside: pulling up the floor to  
replace electrical meters on Russian batteries that aren't charging 
properly, trying to fix a broken U.S. communication system, and 
installing mufflers to reduce the noise inside the Russian-built 
module, Zarya. 
</P>
<P>
	They got started on the repairs within minutes of entering the  
space station. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Aeronautics and Space Administration downplayed the  
multitude of problems coming so soon after the space station's 
launch. 
</P>
<P>
	``In high-tech like this, you're going to have that happen,''  
Mission Control's Milt Heflin explained. 
</P>
<P>
	The shuttle astronauts have until Thursday to unload 3,600  
pounds of spare parts, computers, water and clothes for the men who 
are due to move in next March. 
</P>
<P>
	During Saturday night's spacewalk, Jernigan and Dr. Daniel Barry  
lugged 700 pounds of gear from the shuttle to the station. A pair 
of 5-foot cranes took up most of the load. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though they spent eight hours outside the seven-story-plus  
complex -- 1 1/2 hours longer than planned -- the excursion ended too 
soon for their taste. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't be telling me we're almost done?'' Barry asked when  
it came time to go back in Sunday morning. His next word summed it 
all up: ``Wow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Their spacewalk was just 34 minutes shy of NASA's all-time  
record, an 8 1/2-hour walk back in 1992 in which three astronauts 
grabbed a runaway satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	Jernigan and Barry fell behind when they had to struggle with  
tight screws holding down the Russian-built crane in Discovery's 
cargo bay. Then a camera jammed while they were photographing the 
space station, and they had to get a spare. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the pair were finally back in Discovery's repressurizing  
air lock, Jernigan had trouble connecting her spacesuit to the 
shuttle life-support system. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the snags, Jernigan and Barry accomplished all their  
major chores. About the only thing left undone was a test of NASA's 
newly installed crane; it eventually will be used to haul large 
items around the orbiting outpost. 
</P>
<P>
	``There simply wasn't enough time,'' said Mike Hess, who managed  
the spacewalk from Mission Control. ``We're going to have to rely 
on the fact that we did extensive ground testing before launch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because only two pieces of the Russian crane were installed, a  
test on that unit wasn't needed. The remaining parts, which weren't 
ready for Discovery's flight, will go up on the next shuttle visit 
in December. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the fourth spacewalk on the international space station  
since it was launched in pieces late last year. Altogether, shuttle 
astronauts have spent 29 hours working on the station's exterior, 
mostly back in December. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA estimates 158 more spacewalks, totaling more than 1,000  
hours, will be needed over the next five years to build and 
maintain the station. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990530.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 11:01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Plane Features Safety Parachute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DULUTH, Minn. (AP) -- Alan Klapmeier almost died in 1984 when his  
small plane collided with another in flight, killing the other 
pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	Boris Popov narrowly escaped death in 1977 when a piece broke  
off his hang glider, sending it plummeting 500 feet into a lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Once they got over their harrowing experiences, Klapmeier and  
Popov began to wonder: Why should flying small crafts be so 
dangerous? 
</P>
<P>
	Years after the two men met and began pursuing safer  
alternatives, they believe they have the answer in the Cirrus SR20, 
the first new general aviation plane in almost 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The SR20 comes with the ultimate safety feature: a parachute  
capable of floating the plane to the ground if catastrophe strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Little airplanes have not been built with crashworthiness in  
mind,'' Klapmeier said. ``Ours is the first to accept that 
airplanes will crash.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cirrus Design, based in Duluth, spent $55 million developing the  
SR20, its first product that isn't a kit plane. The company is 
hoping the investment will give it a sizable share of the $5.9 
billion spent annually on general aviation. 
</P>
<P>
	Klapmeier is Cirrus' president. The parachute is supplied by  
Popov's company, Ballistic Recovery Systems of South St. Paul, 
Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	Parachutes on planes aren't a new idea. BRS has sold more than  
14,000 parachutes to pilots who install them on their ultralight 
aircrafts, gliders, kit-built planes and Cessna 150s. 
</P>
<P>
	However, they aren't universally endorsed. Some aviation experts  
believe pilots will hesitate to open the parachutes, which are 
likely to save the passengers but certain to mean the airplane's 
ruin. 
</P>
<P>
	Cirrus, founded in 1984 as a kit-plane maker, says it wants to  
change the way people think and feel about flying in small planes. 
Company officials tout the SR20 as faster, sleeker, more 
comfortable, better-looking and safer than just about any other. 
</P>
<P>
	The company already has more than 290 orders.  
</P>
<P>
	``People are very interested in this airplane,'' said Warren  
Morningstar, a spokesman for the Aircraft Owners and Pilots 
Association, which represents about 345,000 pilots in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the crash of an SR20 test plane in late March, Cirrus  
was sticking to its plan to start delivering planes to customers by 
late spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the crash, which killed the pilot, is under  
investigation. The plane was not equipped with a parachute because 
it wasn't available at the time. The company has since tested 
another airplane off the production line without incident. 
</P>
<P>
	The SR20 is made of composites of fiberglass and epoxy resin  
that allow a more aerodynamic shape than aluminum planes, thus 
increasing airspeed. The SR20 cruises at 160 knots, compared with 
about 120 to 135 knots for other small planes in its category. Its 
maximum flying height is 16,000 feet; its maximum range is 800 
nautical miles. A minimum standard model costs $171,300. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-passenger plane's interior is modeled after the BMW 500  
luxury car series. A fully equipped SR20 has a cellular phone, 
stereo, plush leather seats, and a roomier cabin than typical small 
planes. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane's designers say the SR20 will be easier to fly than  
older planes. 
</P>
<P>
	The dashboard has a 10-inch monitor that displays information  
the pilot would otherwise have to determine from dozens of gauges 
and dials. A single lever controls the throttle and propeller, 
which for anyone who drives a car is roughly equivalent to having 
an automatic tranmission instead of a manual. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best part is landing it. It almost lands itself. You just  
line it up over the runway and it settles down, kind of like 
landing a Buick,'' said Bill Saunders, president of an automotive 
market research firm in Troy, Mich., who expects his SR20 to be 
delivered in August or September. 
</P>
<P>
	Marketing a plane for improved safety hasn't been as easy as it  
seems. The general aviation industry has always believed that 
pilots -- not planes -- should be responsible for their own and their 
passengers' safety. Cirrus' competitors have no plans to place 
parachutes in their planes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not have parachutes on our planes and we have no plans  
to add them,'' said Jan McIntire, spokeswoman for Cessna Aircraft 
Company of Wichita, Kan., the world's largest builder of small 
commercial aviation planes. 
</P>
<P>
	At Lancair, a Bend, Ore., company, that also makes small planes,  
officials don't believe a parachute really makes a plane safer, 
general manager Bob Fair said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Are you going to pull it? Because once you pull it, the  
aircraft is destroyed,'' Fair said. ``Once you pull it, you have no 
control over the aircraft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Popov scoffs at the idea that a pilot wouldn't pull the  
parachute after, say, a midair collision, a heart attack or engine 
failure at 15,000 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the most profound nonsense I've ever heard,'' he said.  
``You're a human being and you're flying a mechanical device. One 
or the other is going to fail at some time. If you have passengers, 
your obligation is to provide as much safety as you possibly can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saunders, who plans to fly his SR20 between his home and  
vacation homes in Jackson Hole, Wyo., and northern Michigan with 
his wife and two daughters, said he would have no problem releasing 
the parachute. 
</P>
<P>
	``I paid $180,000 for my plane, but I guess your life is worth a  
lot more than that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The parachute has been tested in flight eight times and Cirrus  
pronounced the tests a success, although in each one the pilot 
released the parachute and resumed flight without sailing all the 
way to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	To measure the plane's crashworthiness, engineers dropped the  
plane from 10 feet, which simulated impact of about 17 miles per 
hour with a deployed parachute. 
</P>
<P>
	The wing and cabin stayed intact, which Cirrus officials said  
proved a pilot and passengers would survive a crash. But the plane 
couldn't be re-used for another flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Cirrus, a private company, won't release financial data. But  
company officials say they will break even on development costs 
within two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that they're likely to become very successful,'' said  
Al Lange, vice president of Green Tree Financial's Aircraft Group, 
which provides financing to pilots who buy their own planes. 
``Their growth is only limited by their ability to attract 
additional investment capital.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cirrus is not limiting its sales and investment efforts to the  
United States. About 60 of the pre-ordered planes are being 
delivered to overseas customers; the company has sales 
representatives on six continents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
