<HEADLINE> Indy 500 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- More pit crews could be wearing helmets in  
the future. 
</P>
<P>
	A pit row accident in the Indianapolis 500 on Sunday could speed  
the development of helmets being designed and tested by Bell Auto 
Racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Six CART racing teams are using that prototype now, and Bell  
planned to have helmets available to other teams later this year. 
Company officials said Sunday they will work to get the helmets 
ready sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell's general manager, J. Kendall Merrill, said the helmets  
will be free for any racing teams that want them. 
</P>
<P>
                             *--------	 
</P>
<P>
	IT'S MY TURN: During Kenny Brack's post-race news conference,  
the Swedish driver was asked if he felt happier for himself or 
car-owner A.J. Foyt. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy for both of us,'' the blond-haired Brack said,  
glancing at Foyt to his right. Foyt said nothing, and Brack paused 
for a moment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm probably more happy for myself,'' Brack admitted, as Foyt  
started chuckling. ``Because he's won it four times already.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             *--------	 
</P>
<P>
	ENGINE CHANGING: The three cars powered by the Nissan Infiniti  
engines ended the day the same way -- spewing smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	The failure of the engine, which has never won in the Indy  
Racing League, took defending champion Eddie Cheever out of the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheever was running third on the 139th lap when his car started  
smoking and he stopped on the backstretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it went, it just went,'' Cheever said of the Nissan  
engine, which was used by only three of the 33 drivers in the 
field. None of the three finished the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``The engine started smoking really bad, and I just turned it  
off,'' veteran driver Roberto Guerrero said after his Nissan engine 
failed on Lap 105. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Jeret Schroeder -- the third Infiniti driver -- suffered  
the same fate. The other 30 cars in the field used Oldsmobile 
Aurora engines. 
</P>
<P>
	``The engine is incredibly strong,'' said Cheever, the only top  
contender using it. ``We still need to work on its reliability.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	NEW TRADITIONS: Hot rod and motorcycle buff Jay Leno took a ride  
on the famed Speedway -- in the driver's seat of the 2000 Chevrolet 
Monte Carlo pace car. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Tonight Show'' host drove the pace lap to start the race  
before someone took over to handle those duties during caution 
situations the rest of Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just like driving down the L.A. expressway,'' Leno  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Leno had to follow war heros and the latest military  
technology during prerace festivities with a Memorial Day tone. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of servicemen who earned the Medal of Honor, the United  
States' highest distinction for military valor, spun an honorary 
lap around the 2.5-mile track. 
</P>
<P>
	A B-2 Stealth bomber buzzed the track's observation tower  
moments later. The bat-shaped jet drew roars and wows from the 
crowd and racing teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Evangelist Billy Graham, who will lead one of his famed crusades  
in Indianapolis next weekend, offered the prerace prayer. 
</P>
<P>
	``May each driver and team not only be at the peak of the skill,  
but may each be at their moral and spiritual best,'' Graham said. 
``Give everyone a sense of fair play and good sportsmanship and 
protect them from injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	MAYBE NEXT YEAR: Jeff Ward is making progress.  
</P>
<P>
	He was second, just six seconds behind winner Kenny Brack, his  
best finish in three tries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll get this race one day,'' Ward said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ward was third as the rookie of the year in 1997 and 13th last  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted this one bad,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	SLIP SLIDING: The car was not handling well, but Steve Knapp  
tried to push it to a planned pit stop -- just seven laps away. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's rookie of the year didn't make it. The 35-year-old  
driver lost control, slid sideways and slammed into the Turn 2 
wall. 
</P>
<P>
	``The car was a little bit loose and he was trying to drive  
through it to get to the pit stop,'' team owner Bob Hancher said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
