<HEADLINE> Wildfires Burn in Southeast, West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAYLOR, Fla. (AP) -- A 40,000-acre wildfire in north Florida  
burned through portions of the Okefenokee swamp and hopped the 
Florida-Georgia line. 
</P>
<P>
	In California, firefighters braved snakes, scorpions and old  
mine shafts to fight an 11,000-acre fire moving through Joshua Tree 
National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	More firefighters joined exhausted crews Sunday battling two  
large Arizona wildfires threatening ranchers and the endangered 
desert tortoise. 
</P>
<P>
	In far northwestern Arizona, a lightning-sparked fire grew from  
650 acres Saturday to 10,000 acres by nightfall and continued 
moving north on Sunday, Interagency Fire Center spokeswoman Bette 
Arial said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind gusts up to 50 mph helped spread the fire in an area  
between the Arizona-Utah line and Grand Canyon National Park on 
land controlled by the federal Bureau of Land Management. The area 
is known as the Arizona Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	Another lightning wildfire on federal and state land some 80  
miles west of Phoenix near Wenden had burned 5,800 acres as of 
Sunday. The area is home to the endangered desert tortoise. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia fire raged into an area south of the small town of  
Fargo, which lies about eight miles north of the Florida line, said 
Gene Madden, spokesman for the Florida Division of Forestry. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of agencies from both states and the federal government  
are involved in fighting the fire, including the Georgia Division 
of Forestry, the U.S. Forest service and a house of local fire and 
law enforcement agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The California blaze, the largest in the 794,000-acre park's  
history, was 50 percent contained. Though flames were moving west, 
they remained well within the park, said Capt. Jim Wilkins of the 
San Bernardino County Fire Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
