<HEADLINE> Seattle Hotel Implosion Goes Awry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Demolition of a downtown hotel went awry Sunday  
morning and debris from the implosion crashed onto the street 
below, damaging a movie complex, trolley lines and street lights. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured in the explosion-triggered collapse of the  
Waldorf Towers, built in 1903. Eleven blocks were cordoned off 
before the 9 a.m. implosion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Waldorf was rigged to collapse within its site -- about  
one-sixth of a block in size -- following detonation of 175 
explosives loaded into the seven-story structure. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fourth floor buckled out,'' said Doug Hazelrigs,  
construction manager for R.C. Hedreen Co. of Seattle which oversaw 
the project. 
</P>
<P>
	Chunks of concrete, wood and other material broke windows and  
tore through part of the sidewalk canopy at an entertainment 
complex housing Cineplex Odeon and Gameworks, a video arcade. 
</P>
<P>
	Streets were blocked by debris, overhead power lines for  
electric buses on Pike Street were knocked down and at least two 
street lights and a traffic signal were wrecked. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
