<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 23:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Gives Hillary Bit of Advice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sequestered in their vacation home on a  
Florida nature preserve, President Clinton gave his wife, Hillary, 
one bit of advice about the Senate race she is considering: ``You 
have to know, you need to know, why you want the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the first lady has yet to decide whether to seek  
the seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. But 
he said he would support her wholeheartedly if she did run. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever she's for, I'm for,'' Clinton told reporters Sunday  
as Air Force One flew back to Washington. When asked whether the 
family would take another vacation later this summer in New York 
state, he said, ``I'll go wherever she wants to go. From now on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is barred by the Constitution from serving a third term,  
but he said, ``If I could run again, I would. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I'm not unhappy about it. I'm actually looking forward to  
being a person again. ... I never had a day in my life where I was 
unhappy. I always knew what I wanted to do, I was happy doing it, 
and every day was good to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had not decided what he'll do when leaves the White  
House in 2001, ``but I've got a lot of ideas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In talking to his wife about the Senate, Clinton said, ``I gave  
her probably the advice I gave everybody: You have to know, you 
need to know, why you want the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to be able to tell somebody in 30 seconds, you have  
to be able to tell somebody in five minutes, you have to be able to 
give a 30-minute talk,'' he said. ``I got elected president because 
I knew, I had a very good idea what I wanted to do, and I think 
it's very important. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that consultants, and the polls, all that stuff, it's  
all very important. But the most important thing is that you know 
why you want to serve. It makes the effort of the campaign worth 
it, and it makes the risk of losing bearable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For 15 candid minutes, Clinton discussed an array of topics,  
from the various animals he saw at the White Oak Plantation in 
Yulee, Fla., to the new Nigerian president and polishing up his 
golf game with three young pros who work at White Oak. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had the best round of my life the other day. I had a 75,''  
Clinton said, then quickly added that his young instructors let him 
take a ``mulligan,'' or a do-over shot. But as good as his score 
was, he said, the others shot 66, 67 and 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, Clinton said he enjoyed the five-day vacation, and  
didn't miss the scrutiny of the Washington press corps, ``but don't 
take that in a negative way.'' He said he took delight in feeding 
pine cones to eight black rhinos, who ate them ``for roughage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, the president bounced up and down to playfully  
simulate the effect of riding on the bumpy, unpaved road that led 
up to White Oak. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons capped their five-day vacation Sunday by  
participating in an annual retreat by the Progressive Foundation, a 
branch of the Democratic Leadership Council. This year's topic was 
``The Politics of the Third Way,'' a term moderate Democrats have 
coined for Clinton's blend of restrained economic policies and 
liberal social agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation said the retreat, which was closed to the press,  
focused on the challenges the third way faces ``in this country and 
worldwide,'' defining the philosophy as the embodiment of ``equal 
opportunity for all, special privilege for none.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to one attendee, Mrs. Clinton offered no hint at a  
morning meeting about her Senate decision. But a longtime adviser 
to the first lady said the longer she waits to make an official 
move, the more likely it was that she would run. Otherwise, other 
potential Democratic candidates would be cheated of time. 
</P>
<P>
	The next step would be forming an exploratory committee in July  
to cover the costs of unofficial campaigning in New York. A bid for 
the seat in 2000 likely will cost $15 million or more. 
</P>
<P>
	James Carville, who managed the president's 1992 campaign, said  
Sunday on CNN's ``Late Edition'' that he expects Mrs. Clinton to 
run. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything I know and conversations I've had with any number  
of people, the first lady included, indicates to me that this is 
something that she really wants to do,'' Carville said. ``I expect 
her to mount a heck of an effective campaign ... And I expect her 
to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One concern has been how Mrs. Clinton would handle the increased  
scrutiny she would come under once she was the candidate, and not 
just the candidate's wife. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview published Sunday in The New York Times Magazine,  
the first lady said she was prepared for such scrutiny given the 
pressures the Clintons have weathered from the Whitewater 
investigation through the Monica Lewinsky scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has crossed my mind. But the possibility of partisan or  
political attacks does not serve as a deterrent,'' she said. ``That 
is not anything that would prevent me, after having been through 
what we've been through, from deciding to run for office.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
