<DOCNO> APW19990530.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 12:51:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schilling Is Complete Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Curt Schilling has a long way to go before  
approaching the exploits of ``Old Hoss'' Radbourn, who pitched 73 
complete games in 1884. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, in this era of five-inning starters and career-ending arm  
injuries, Schilling's five straight complete games are nothing 
short of amazing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia Phillies ace lived up to his menacing aura yet  
again Friday night with a four-hit shutout for his fifth 
consecutive complete game. He has six this season, not only leading 
the majors individually but surpassing every other team in both 
leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why we have no intention of ever letting him go,''  
Phillies manager Terry Francona said. ``That's why teams are 
clamoring for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling (8-2) did more than pitch his first shutout of the  
season and 13th of his career in the Phillies' 2-0 victory over 
Colorado. He did so by blowing away Larry Walker, Dante Bichette 
and Vinny Castilla with pitches approaching 100 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	And he did so less than a week after the worst ninth-inning  
collapse of his career. Last Sunday in New York, Schilling 
inexplicably squandered a 4-0 lead in a 5-4 loss to the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Seemingly addicted to big-game pressure, Schilling needs little  
to get motivated. The memory of that crushing defeat was more than 
enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, it motivated me,'' said Schilling, who struck out nine  
and walked one. ``How could it not? To lose a game like that all by 
yourself is tough. It was a tough five days for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a tougher nine innings for the Rockies.  
</P>
<P>
	After walking No. 8 hitter Chris Petersen to load the bases with  
two outs in the second, Schilling retired 22 of the last 24 batters 
and capped it with a ninth inning that showed his true zeal for 
finishing. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling struck out Walker, second in the NL with a .373  
average, on a 96 mph fastball. After throwing in the 92-93 mph 
range for the first eight innings, he engaged Bichette in a battle 
of pure power. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a ton left,'' Schilling said. ``I reached back for a  
lot. I threw him everything I had, and they were some of the best 
pitches I threw all night. Five or six times, I felt like I was 
going to get him but he kept getting the bat on the ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bichette fouled off seven of Schilling's first 12 pitches before  
going down swinging on a 98 mph heater. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a horse, man,'' Bichette said. ``Just a horse.''  
</P>
<P>
	After Bichette's marathon, Schilling quickly disposed of  
Castilla on three pitches. The last one was a nasty 93 mph 
splitter, his 135th pitch of the game. On the Phillies' bench, Paul 
Byrd said, ``I thought we were going to the World Series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd, who spent time on the Atlanta staff with Greg Maddux and  
Tom Glavine, tried to compare Schilling's ninth inning to a 
different kind of dominance enjoyed by his former teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like Mark McGwire vs. Tony Gwynn,'' Byrd said. ``When  
McGwire hits a ball, it's something that other people can't do. 
Maddux is a great pitcher, and Glavine is a great pitcher. But 
Schilling did something in the ninth inning that no one else can 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the days of knickers and mitten-like gloves, pitchers  
finished just about every game they started. Radbourn completed all 
73 of his starts in 1884. At a time when home runs were almost as 
unheard of as helmet cams, the ``Hoss'' had a 60-12 record and 1.38 
ERA 
</P>
<P>
	Heck, Babe Ruth led the American League with 35 complete games  
for Boston in 1917. Walter Johnson completed 36 of 37 starts in 
1911. 
</P>
<P>
	In the modern era, the Phillies' Robin Roberts pitched 28  
straight complete games in 1953 and finished the season with 33. 
Steve Carlton's career-high was 30 in 1972, that awesome season in 
which he had 27 of the Phillies' 59 victories. 
</P>
<P>
	How times have changed. Schilling led the NL with 15 complete  
games last season, and Baltimore's Scott Erickson led the AL with 
11. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do know that I run into a lot more guys that have a smile on  
their face when get pulled after six innings winning 4-1 than guys 
that are angry,'' Schilling said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two other pitchers this decade have pitched five  
consecutive complete games. Pat Hentgen did it for Toronto in 1996 
en route to a Cy Young Award. Philadelphia's Tommy Greene did it in 
1993 en route to a sore arm that derailed his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Arm injuries are rampant. Cubs right-hander Kerry Wood is out  
for the year after major elbow surgery. Last week, Tampa Bay's Tony 
Saunders became the latest in a disturbing string of left-handed 
pitchers who have mysteriously broken their arms throwing a pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Schilling, the ``Iron Horse'' of the mound, had shoulder  
surgery in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet he keeps on pitching, and finishing what he started.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
