<DOCNO> APW19990530.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 13:41:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teamsters Strike Looms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- The Teamsters and new car haulers were  
still far apart Sunday on major issues such as pay for new workers 
and pensions as a strike deadline loomed early Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Teamsters President James P. Hoffa said the union was ready to  
strike when its current contract expires at 12:01 a.m. EDT Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have made it very clear to management that their  
unacceptable demands to hire part-time workers, to cut pay for new 
employees, and to use Mexican trucks would all trigger a strike,'' 
Hoffa said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations began in February between the Teamsters,  
representing 12,800 workers in the contract dispute, and the 
National Automobile Transporters Association, which is made up of 
17 companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The union could target one or all of the companies that contract  
with automakers to move new cars to dealers from assembly plants, 
ports and rail yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Duchesne, a spokesman for the association, said the two  
sides had made some progress on equipment and safety matters, but 
there were still ``substantial differences on the major issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those include union objections to industry proposals to give  
entry-level workers lower salaries and use part-time workers and 
Mexican truckers, and union demands for better pensions and health 
care and higher wage increases than management is offering. 
</P>
<P>
	``The companies are flush with money because of the productivity  
of our drivers so there will be no better opportunity to get a fair 
slice of the economic pie,'' said Hoffa, who took over the 
Teamsters in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The car haulers say the Teamsters are the highest-paid truckers  
at $68,000 on average, and contend that labor costs are rising 
faster than what the hauling companies can charge automakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides met separately Sunday afternoon to consider  
proposals put forth in earlier talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Duchesne said he expected the talks to continue well into the  
night Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
