<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italy: Murdoch Welcome in TV Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italy's communication minister said Sunday he  
welcomed Australian-born media magnate Rupert Murdoch's minority 
entry to the country's Pay-TV market, saying, ``In Italy, there's 
room for all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia SpA signed a deal Saturday to sell 65 percent of  
its digital pay-TV unit, Stream, to a group of companies including 
Murdoch's News Corp., for $70 million. 
</P>
<P>
	News Corp. will take a 35 percent stake, Italy's Cecchi Gori  
group 18 percent, and SDS, a company formed by four Italian soccer 
clubs, 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Murdoch has been trying to gain entry to Italy's pay-TV field  
for some time, setting off protests by some in government and media 
about feared foreign control of sports, information and 
entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``In an essential service like television, in Italy, there's  
room for all,'' as long as the service overall remains essentially 
Italian, Communications Minister Salvatore Cardinale said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Murdoch enters within a group that's predominantly national,''  
Cardinale stressed. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Communications Undersecretary Vincenzo Vita said  
Murdoch was welcome as long as he showed ``rigorous respect for 
Italian rules and laws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's signing ratified a deal announced in April. Olivetti  
SpA's successful takeover of Telecom Italia delayed the sale 
slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	Stream is Italy's second-largest digital TV operator, with an  
estimated 120,000 subscribers. The number is expected to increase 
since the platform now will also offer popular soccer games. 
</P>
<P>
	Stream already has the encoded broadcast rights for games played  
by the Fiorentina, Lazio, Parma and Roma soccer clubs from 1999 to 
2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
