<HEADLINE> De La Hoya-Trinidad Gets Green Light </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The monetary dispute in the camp of  
IBF champion Felix ``Tito'' Trinidad was resolved Sunday, giving 
the green light to the Sept. 18 date for a welterweight unification 
with WBC champion Oscar De La Hoya. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything turned out as we wished. In the end, we will  
present the match that all the world wants to see,'' promoter Don 
King said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Felix Trinidad Sr., the fighter's father and manager, was not as  
happy with Sunday's deal, which gives Trinidad $8.5 million and 
King $2 million. In addition, King is to pay Trinidad $300,000 for 
training costs and both men get an additional $4 each for every 
pay-per-view customer over 850,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly I could have negotiated a better contract ... but it's  
the match that all the world wants to see and the time has come. 
It's past time for Tito to confront Oscar De La Hoya and knock him 
out to show for real who is the best,'' Trinidad Sr. said after 6 1/2 
hours of negotiations Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad is a little-known fighter from Puerto Rico with an  
impressive 35-0 record that he upheld Saturday night with his 30th 
knockout, this one of Colombia's Hugo Pineda on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya is 31-0 with 22 knockouts and will earn $15 million  
from the Sept. 18 fight at Mandalay Bay Hotel in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the initial deal, Trinidad was to get $8 million and King  
$2 million. Trinidad's camp had been squabbling over an additional 
$500,000 agreed to by De La Hoya's promoter Bob Arum. Trinidad Sr. 
was holding out in clear expectation of a record number of 
pay-per-view customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad was confident after Saturday's fight.  
</P>
<P>
	``This was an important triumph on the way to my greatest  
challenge,'' he said. ``This was a way for me to demonstrate to (De 
La Hoya) I'm ready for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad had lost 18 pounds over two months to qualify for his  
division, weighing in at 147 pounds Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya hurt his hand when he defended his title May 24  
against Oba Carr, but after finding it was only sprained said he 
would have time to recuperate before getting into training to face 
Trinidad. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's get it on,'' De La Hoya said. ``It will be the fight of  
the century.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
