<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 18:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers' Jackson Misses Key Shots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Mark Jackson was feeling no panic over  
Indiana's loss in the opening game of the Eastern Conference finals 
with New York, 93-90 setback that came as he missed two key shots 
over the final 31 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	The first miss came from the free throw line with the score tied  
88-88. Antonio Davis was called for a loose ball foul on the miss, 
sending Patrick Ewing to the free throw line where he hit two foul 
shots to put the Knicks ahead to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, with New York holding a 93-90 lead and the Pacers filling  
the court with potential 3-point shooters, Jackson tossed up an 
airball as time expired. His foot was close to the line as he shot, 
but whether it was a 2- or 3-point attempt became moot when it 
missed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just wasn't meant to be,'' said Jackson, who had predicted  
an Indiana victory in the best-of-7 series before it began. ``We 
made mistakes, missed shots, missed foul shots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The loss ended a 12-game playoff winning streak for Indiana at  
Market Square Arena, a run that included three over Chicago in the 
conference finals last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were playing zone. Spree (Latrell Sprewell) was playing  
center field and Allan (Houston) was all over me. Mark had a decent 
look at it. It really didn't matter who took it, we had a lot of 
guys out there who could have hit that shot,'' said Reggie Miller, 
who led Indiana with 19 points and also missed a key 3-pointer in 
the final minute that would have given Indiana the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was trying to get a 3 up,'' Jackson said. ``It didn't go in,  
but I can live with the look. I missed some chippies, missed some 
easy ones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Game 2 is Tuesday night.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we played hard, no question about that. We've just  
got to continue to keep on working, we'll be fine,'' Jackson said. 
``There's no panic in this lockerroom. Give them credit, they won 
game one. ... We didn't get the job done early on. They played 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The misses in the final minutes took the luster off Jackson's  
play against the Knicks, a team he won rookie of the year honors 
for and played with for five years. In 31 minutes, Jackson had 11 
assists, seven rebounds and one turnover while scoring six points 
on 1-of-8 shooting from the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``They won the ballgame. We're not going to win every game,''  
Jackson said. ``We're a veteran team, no panic here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana lost despite outrebounding the Knicks 41-39 and  
outshooting them from the field. A key difference was behind the 
3-point line and fast-break points. New York was 6-of-12 and 
Indiana just 3-of-9 from behind the arc and the Knicks had a 22-8 
advantage in fast-break points. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll look forward to Tuesday. We still feel we're going to  
win it,'' Jackson said. 
</P>
<P>
	To do that, Indiana will also look for a stronger performance  
from center Rik Smits, who was 4-of-12 from the field and played 
only 26 minutes before fouling out with 7:38 to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had some open looks, but they just didn't fall. Two or three  
looks I did get, I was double-teamed and another one I missed,'' 
said Smits, who finished with 12 points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
