<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 13:11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Venus Didn't Do Her Homework </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Next time she faces an obscure player at a Grand  
Slam, Venus Williams might consider a little homework. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams admitted she didn't do that with Barbara Schwartz. Now  
the 125th-ranked Austrian is in the quarterfinals and Williams is 
out the door. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, who lost 2-6, 7-6 (9-7), 6-3, said she had never seen  
Schwartz play and knew virtually nothing about her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was occupied playing my own matches,'' said Williams, seeded  
fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether she should have tried to learn something of her  
opponent, Williams said: ``It's a possibility, but it didn't 
happen. What can I say? 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't really know who exactly I was playing. I didn't watch  
the draw so much, so I didn't really know,'' she said. ``I mean 
what's the difference? You go out there and compete, you play the 
ball, you play the point. I have to be prepared with my game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Top-seeded Martina Hingis said it's ``dangerous'' not to know  
much about an opponent. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why it came out that way, I guess,'' she said. ``I just  
don't go into a match not knowing what is going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No. 2 Lindsay Davenport said she always tries to get information  
on the strengths and weaknesses of her opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the round of 16, you can't take anybody lightly,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwartz shouldn't have been such an unknown quantity.  
</P>
<P>
	True, the 20-year-old Austrian was still at school last year.  
But she won a set against Steffi Graf at the Australian Open this 
year and was one of the biggest first-round surprises at this 
year's French by beating 13th-seeded Dominique van Roost. 
</P>
<P>
	She downed Nathalie Dechy, another top 30 player, in the third  
round. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss was a huge blow to Williams, who like her sister Serena  
was supremely confident of winning her first Grand Slam at Roland 
Garros. 
</P>
<P>
	She was brilliant coming into the tournament, having won 21 of  
her last 22 matches and consecutive clay-court titles at the German 
and Italian opens. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams had three match points against Schwartz in the second  
set, but suddenly began to struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwartz, serving at 5-6, 0-40, won five straight points. At  
that stage, Williams was still upbeat, saying she thought 
```tiebreak, I am going to win this match.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But then everything unraveled.  
</P>
<P>
	``Suddenly, before I knew it, it was the third set,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	In the tiebreaker, Williams hit a forehand into the net to give  
Schwartz the set. In the third, Schwartz broke three times. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first Grand Slam that I haven't got to the  
quarterfinals. That's kind of odd,'' Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hingis admitted she was relieved Williams lost.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is very surprising that Barbara beat Venus,'' she said.  
``I'm happy about that result, that I don't have to play Venus. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I saw the draw with both of them on my side I thought, I  
am really going to have to work if I want to win this tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Williams wasn't too despondent at her loss.  
</P>
<P>
	``Usually, when I lose a match I really beat myself. But this  
time I really think she came out and played well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990530.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 06:11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Leaves Inner City to Ivy League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cedric Jennings has known two very different  
lives: the violence and fear of this city's roughest, poorest 
neighborhoods and the privileged, ivy-covered walls of Brown 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Where he goes after graduating Monday from Brown remains an open  
question. 
</P>
<P>
	``I live in two worlds,'' says Jennings, 21. ``I have to turn  
the way I address people on and off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This tall, self-assured young man, plucked from obscurity to be  
the hero of a Pulitzer Prize-winning series in The Wall Street 
Journal and a subsequent book by author Ron Suskind, now looks 
forward to a new adventure -- possibly working in advertising or the 
music industry, perhaps in California. 
</P>
<P>
	He appreciates the praise he has received from Washington's  
mayor for his long journey from a rough place. But it is not enough 
to persuade him to return to a city where the memories are not that 
great. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were always ducking bullets,'' Jennings said of his  
childhood in southeast Washington, just a few miles from Capitol 
but a universe removed. 
</P>
<P>
	School was no safe haven. ``There were a lot of fights,'' he  
said. ``I can remember the blood drop trail on the way to school 
after someone was stabbed. It still haunts me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In some ways, journeying home from Brown has become almost as  
difficult as going to college for the first time four years ago, 
even though Jennings says he enjoys visiting his mother, who still 
lives here. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of people at home consider me a smart person,  
but they don't care about that as long as I'm down to earth,'' 
Jennings says. 
</P>
<P>
	Suskind shadowed Jennings during part of his high school and  
college years to tell the story of an ``undercover honors student'' 
at an urban school where being smart makes you a target of bullies. 
</P>
<P>
	The reporter says he was surprised to hear how often people told  
the youngster to remain humble. When Suskind first approached a 
school administrator about interviewing Jennings, the school 
official said the honors student ``has got a quick tongue and is 
too proud.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such comments used to bother Jennings, but they do not seem to  
anymore. ``Since when is being proud of academic success a crime?'' 
he asks. 
</P>
<P>
	Dodging bullets and fists and getting Ivy League school grades  
is no small feat for a kid from Jennings' neighborhood, said 
Suskind, who lives in a manicured part of Northwest Washington. 
``We really are two cities, but maybe we don't have to be,'' 
Suskind said. 
</P>
<P>
	That is the way the city's new mayor, Anthony Williams, says he  
sees things, too. He pointed to Jennings' story during his 
inaugural address as all that is good about Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cedric's tenacious struggle to achieve acceptance to Brown  
University shows you everything you need to know about our 
community's passionate, ingrained hope in the unseen,'' Williams 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the mayor gave that kind of speech to young people, he might  
inspire more of them to make something of their lives, Suskind 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A chemistry teacher at Ballou served as Jennings' principal male  
role model because his father was in and out of prison on drug 
charges. His mother, Barbara Jennings, raised him by herself. 
</P>
<P>
	As with many other experiences, Jennings used it in his academic  
pursuits, writing his senior thesis on the role fathers play in the 
academic success of boys in inner cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennings says he is not misunderstood at Brown, unlike his high  
school days. 
</P>
<P>
	But college was an adjustment. In his freshman year, Jennings  
fell behind other students who had gone to better high schools. 
Eventually, his falling grades prompted him to seek tutoring, which 
helped. But he wishes the university had provided remedial classes 
and more emotional support, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Jennings expects to graduate with a 3.4 grade point average  
and a major in education with an emphasis on math. He turned down 
an offer from a leading investment banking firm in hopes of finding 
something in advertising or music. 
</P>
<P>
	He volunteers at a city school in Providence, R.I., Brown's  
home, and says one day he would like to turn his energy toward 
teaching. Jennings also enjoys talking with other young people 
about the book and finds it ironic he has gone from being a misfit 
to a role model. 
</P>
<P>
	Readers may have worried about him as they turned the pages of  
Suskind's book, ``A Hope in the Unseen: An American Odyssey from 
the Inner City to the Ivy League,'' but there seems little cause 
for concern now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not only hopeful, I'm more empowered,'' said Jennings.  
``I'm more assured that I'm going to be OK.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
