<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Jets Pound Serb Forces  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- As NATO makes good on its pledge to  
pound Yugoslavia with airstrikes, European leaders are looking to 
revive their quest for a diplomatic solution. NATO said Saturday it 
had hit hard at Serb forces in Kosovo during the previous 24 hours, 
attacking tanks and artillery pieces, as well as airfields and 
other targets across Yugoslavia. Local media reported that six 
people were killed today. Serbian media reported more civilian 
casualties, including two deaths in the village of Cumurjila 
outside Nis in central Serbia. 

</P>
<P>
	No End in Sight for Kashmir Fighting  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- Indian army spokesman Maj. Gen. J.J. Singh  
says ground fighting in the disputed region of Kashmir could last 
for several weeks before the military regains control over the 
area. The air force began sorties Wednesday aimed at infiltrators 
entrenched in Indian territory in Kashmir. New Delhi says they 
include Afghan mercenaries and Pakistan army soldiers disguised as 
guerrillas. Meanwhile, India's prime minister won the backing of 
political rivals on the airstrikes and said he had rejected a 
suggestion by his Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz Sharif, to end the 
military action in the divided territory, claimed by both of the 
nuclear nations. 

</P>
<P>
	Vitter Wins Louisiana Race  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Former state Rep. David Vitter was elected  
Saturday night as Bob Livingston's successor in Congress, winning a 
close election over former Gov. Dave Treen. With 99 percent of the 
precincts reporting, Vitter got 60,699 votes, or 51 percent, to 
Treen's 58,825 votes, or 49 percent. The two solidly conservative 
Republican lawyers, both veteran politicians, struggled to point 
out their differences after they were the top finishers in a field 
of nine in a May 1 primary. Vitter, 38, hoped to use youth to his 
advantage, saying the 70-year-old Treen's influence would be 
diminished because of his age. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Prosecutors Request Tripp Tapes  
</P>
<P>
	ELLICOTT CITY, Md. (AP) -- Maryland prosecutors have asked the  
federal judge overseeing a grand jury investigation of President 
Clinton for access to Linda Tripp's secret tape recordings of 
Monica Lewinsky, The Baltimore Sun reported Saturday. State 
prosecutors filed the request with U.S. District Judge Norma 
Holloway Johnson, unidentified sources told the paper. A Maryland 
grand jury is considering whether Mrs. Tripp broke Maryland law by 
recording conversations with Ms. Lewinsky. If tried and convicted, 
she could get five years in prison and a $10,000 fine. 

</P>
<P>
	New Nigerian Leader Takes Office  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Promising that ``we shall not fail,''  
Olusegun Obasanjo today became Nigeria's first civilian president 
in 15 years, ending a string of disastrous military regimes that 
crippled this African giant. Thousands of spectators cheered as 
Obasanjo embraced the outgoing military ruler, Gen. Abdulsalami 
Abubakar, who guided the 11-month transition that brought Nigeria 
from brutal dictatorship to democracy. Obasanjo pledged to rebuild 
a nation left in squalor despite billions of dollars in oil wealth. 

</P>
<P>
	Mariners Bury Devil Rays 11-5  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- David Segui hit a double and triple and scored  
three runs to lead the surging Seattle Mariners to an 11-5 victory 
over the struggling Tampa Bay Devil Rays on Saturday night. Segui 
continued to feast on Tampa Bay pitching. After going 2-for-3 with 
two walks, two RBI and three runs scored Saturday night, he is now 
hitting .429 (27-for-63) in his career against the Devil Rays. 
Mariners starter Jeff Fassero (3-6) was struck in the left hand by 
a line drive hit by Herbert Perry with two outs in the fifth 
inning. Fassero managed to finish the inning to qualify for the 
win, but did not return for the sixth. 

</P>
<P>
	Angels Edge Royals 4-3  
</P>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Steve Sparks pitched no-hit ball for 5  
1-3 innings and shutout ball for eight until needing ninth-inning 
relief help, and the Anaheim Angels held on to beat the Kansas City 
Royals 4-3 Saturday night. Sparks (2-4) appeared to be in complete 
control going into the ninth with a 4-0 lead, but gave up two hits 
and a walk with one out and left the game in the hands of Troy 
Percival. The Anaheim closer gave up a bases-clearing double to 
Scott Pose before getting the last two outs for his 13th save in 14 
opportunities. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
</P>
