<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 18:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thomas Coffin    	
</P>
<P>
	STANTON, Calif. (AP) -- Thomas E. Coffin, an NBC researcher whose  
studies during the infancy of the television age showed the impact 
of advertising, died May 13. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffin conducted scientific studies that showed that people  
bought products after seeing them in television commercials. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all talk about it today as a given that people see  
television and act on it. But he was the first to document and 
quantify the effectiveness of advertising on television,'' said 
Nicholas Schiavone, NBC senior vice president of television network 
research. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffin had been a psychology professor at Hofstra University  
until he left to become the network's market research specialist in 
1949. 
</P>
<P>
	His groundbreaking research, known as the Hofstra studies, found  
that brand awareness was ``hundreds of percent higher'' among TV 
owners, said Bill Rubens, who succeeded Coffin as head of NBC's 
research department. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffin was NBC's director of research from 1964 to 1972, then  
became a consultant for the network until his retirement in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife and three nieces and nephews.  

</P>
<P>
 *Ralph Geffen    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ralph J. Geffen, a federal magistrate who  
ordered the release of papers that documented the FBI's efforts to 
monitor gay rights organizations, died Wednesday after a two-month 
battle with cancer. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Geffen ruled in 1988 that there was no ``plausible law  
enforcement basis'' for the FBI's surveillance and infiltration 
operations, conducted for more than 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Undercover probes by the FBI using paid informers were ``based  
upon the anti-homosexual bias of the late FBI Director J. Edgar 
Hoover and his belief that homosexuals, especially when organized 
or joining in groups, posed a threat'' to national security, Geffen 
said in his ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI released more than 5,800 pages of documents, but many  
files were withheld and passages were blacked out on those that 
were released. 
</P>
<P>
	His ruling was made in a 1983 lawsuit filed by the American  
Civil Liberties Union. 

</P>
<P>
 *William R. Lawley Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Retired Air Force Col. William R. Lawley  
Jr., who was awarded the Medal of Honor for bringing a badly 
damaged World War II bomber back to base despite his wounds, died 
Sunday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawley was a 24-year-old lieutenant when he participated in the  
Feb. 20, 1944 raid on German aircraft centers -- the largest raid on 
the continent at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	As Lawley's plane was coming off the target in Liepzig, Germany,  
it was attacked by 20 enemy fighters. Eight crew members, including 
the co-pilot, were killed, and the brand-new B-17 bomber was 
severely crippled, one engine on fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawley suffered serious wounds around his face, according to his  
citation, but forced the co-pilot's body off the controls and 
brought the plane out of a steep dive. 

</P>
<P>
 *Harry Melling    	
</P>
<P>
	GAYLORD, Mich. (AP) -- Harry Melling, president of Melling Tool  
Co. and owner of the NASCAR team on which Bill Elliott enjoyed his 
greatest success, died Saturday of a heart attack. He was 54. 
</P>
<P>
	Melling was in his 20th year of NASCAR Winston Cup Racing.  
Melling Racing won the Winston Cup points championship with Elliott 
behind the wheel in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Three years earlier, Melling's team won a then-record $1 million  
bonus -- the Winston Million -- from R.J. Reynolds for winning three 
of the four major races on the Winston Cup schedule that year -- the 
Daytona 500, the Winston 500 and the Southern 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott drove for the team from 1981-92, getting 34 of his 40  
career victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Winston Cup Scene, the leading publication covering stock car  
racing, in 1997 named Melling one of the 40 most important people 
in NASCAR history. 
</P>
<P>
	Melling was the grandson of George Melling Sr., who founded  
Melling Tool in Jackson, in 1944. The firm grew to become a leading 
supplier of oil pumps. 

</P>
<P>
 *Joao Carlos de Oliveira    	
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Joao Carlos de Oliveira, who held the  
world triple jump record for a decade, died Saturday after a 
monthlong battle with lung and liver ailments. He was 45. 
</P>
<P>
	The body of the Brazilian sports hero was taken to the  
Legislative Assembly in Sao Paulo on Sunday and draped in the 
national flag. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliveira was in a car accident in 1981 and his right leg had to  
be amputated. His car was hit head-on by the car of a drunken 
driver going the wrong way at night on a highway. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1975, he set the world record with a jump of 58 feet, 8 1/4  
inches at the Pan American Games in Mexico, a mark that stood for 
10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He also won bronze medals in the 1976 and 1980 Olympics, and  
Brazilians dubbed him ``Joao do Pulo'' -- Portuguese for ``Jumping 
John.'' 

</P>
<P>
 *Raphael Recanati    	
</P>
<P>
	TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- Israeli business magnate Raphael  
Recanati, former chairman of one of Israel's largest banks and 
founder of a shipping company that brought vital supplies to the 
fledgling state, died Friday at his home in New York. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Recanati was born in Greece in 1924 and left for pre-state  
Palestine in 1935 with his family, which founded Israel Discount 
Bank. He enlisted in the Jewish militia Palmach and was sent to 
Egypt, where he worked to help Egyptian Jews reach Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	When the state was established in 1948, he founded the shipping  
company Israel-America Line, which brought badly needed food and 
weapons to Israel. Recanati served as chair of Israel Discount Bank 
from 1982 until 1986, when a Jerusalem court sentenced him to eight 
months in prison for fraudulent business dealings. The sentence was 
reversed on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Recanati moved to New York, where he founded and headed foreign  
subsidiaries of the bank. 
  	   	
</P>
