<HEADLINE> Report: Indian Scientist Expelled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government expelled an Indian scientist  
who worked in a U.S. weapons lab because he was connected with 
India's nuclear-weapons program, Newsweek reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine did not report the scientist's name or reveal its  
sources for the man's removal from the Los Alamos National 
Laboratory in New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year Los Alamos expelled an Indian scientist when it was  
discovered he had ties to India's nuclear-bomb program,'' Newsweek 
said it has learned. 
</P>
<P>
	It did not characterize his relationship with India's program.  
It detonated what it characterized as a peaceful nuclear device in 
1974 and set off a round of tests last year that prompted 
neighboring Pakistan to reply with nuclear weapons tests of its 
own. 
</P>
<P>
	The scientist was among around 17 foreign nationals who worked  
in the highly classified nuclear-weapons division at Los Alamos, 
Newsweek said. Others were from India, Russia, China and Israel, it 
said, and laboratory officials said none had access to classified 
information. 
</P>
