<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hyde Thinks Gun Bill Will Pass House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVO, Utah (AP) -- The House will likely pass a package of  
gun-control measures approved last week by the Senate and could go 
even further, Rep. Henry Hyde said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see the Senate bill at least (passing in the House) ... and  
maybe more,'' said Hyde, the chairman of the House Judiciary 
Committee. ``But the bill will deal with much more than just gun 
control. It'll deal with entertainment and that sort of thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Research is being done to find out what limits Congress can  
constitutionally impose on television, movies and music, Hyde told 
The Salt Lake Tribune in a story in Sunday's edition. The Illinois 
Republican did not elaborate on what the limits might be, but said 
House Republican leaders will ``have them early next week'' for 
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	The entertainment industry has come under siege by lawmakers and  
others for its violent movies and video games in the wake of school 
shootings in Littleton, Colo., and Conyers, Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate legislation would require background checks of buyers  
at gun shows, would ban the importing of high-capacity ammunition 
clips and would require guns be equipped with childproof safety 
devices. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde was in Provo speaking at a fund-raiser for Rep. Chris  
Cannon, R-Utah. Hyde said he was skeptical that new gun laws are 
the answer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is a spiritual vacuum ... New gun laws are not  
going to change that,'' he said. ``That isn't to say there isn't 
the need for some new amendments.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
