<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stampede in Minsk Leaves 54 Dead  
</P>
<P>
	MINSK, Belarus (AP) -- State radio is reporting Monday that 54  
people were killed when a crowd stampeded in a pedestrian 
passageway following a rock concert. About 100 others were injured. 
The incident occurred late Sunday night after a concert and 
festival marking the two-year anniversary of the Mir radio station. 
According to police and health officials, the crush occurred in a 
pedestrian tunnel near the Nemiga metro station not far from the 
center of the city. The ITAR-Tass news agency said 2,000 people 
leaving the concert near the city Sports Palace had dashed into the 
underpass when a heavy rain began. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Missiles Hit Bridge  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO missiles slammed into a bridge  
crowded with civilians on their way to market Sunday leaving 11 
dead, state-run Yugoslavian media reports. Several cars plunged 
into the Velika Morava River after three missiles struck the bridge 
used by shoppers going to and from a market near the town of 
Krusevac, Tanjug news agency reported. Divers were searching for 
victims, the news agency said, adding that the attack wounded 40 
people, including five in critical condition. 

</P>
<P>
	Astronauts Enter Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Discovery's astronauts swung open  
the hatches of the international space station Sunday night and 
floated into the chilly but brightly lit outpost. They were the 
first visitors in six months. Before the seven shuttle astronauts 
began opening the doors, flight controllers warned it would be 57 
degrees in the first module, the American-made Unity. The 
astronauts will spend the next three days making repairs and 
deliveries to the 240-mile-high station, vacant since December. 
It's bigger and far more tedious work than what they did earlier 
Sunday during the second-longest spacewalk ever -- rigging cranes 
and other tools to the exterior. 

</P>
<P>
	Colombian Rebels Abandon Hostages  
</P>
<P>
	CALI, Colombia (AP) -- Leftist Colombian rebels masquerading as  
soldiers abducted about 100 churchgoers Sunday, but later abandoned 
at least 79 of them after army troops and police commandos began 
pursuit. Just as the weekly Roman Catholic children's Mass was 
ending at the rustic La Maria church, about 30 uniformed rebels 
forced the worshippers out of the wooden pews and on to two 
canvas-covered trucks and drove them out of the southern 
residential district of Ciudad Jardin. The rebels, who shot and 
killed the bodyguard of one of the churchgoers, belonged to the 
National Liberation Army, or ELN, Colombia's second-largest rebel 
band, authorities said. 

</P>
<P>
	Energy Dept. Firings Expected  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said Sunday  
he would fire department officials for failing to act on signs 
China was stealing secrets from a U.S. nuclear weapons lab. 
Dismissals and demotions could come as early as this week, after 
Richardson receives an internal report on security lapses at the 
Los Alamos lab in New Mexico that may have contributed to China's 
thefts of U.S. nuclear secrets. Richardson said China got 
information on three nuclear warheads but there is no evidence 
China has used that information to modernize or deploy nuclear 
weapons. 

</P>
<P>
	Great Pyramid Reopens This Week  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- The largest of the three ancient Giza  
Pyramids will reopen this week after workers cleaned up graffiti, 
mended cracks and installed new lighting and ventilation systems. 
The restoration of the Great Pyramid, built as a tomb for King 
Cheops about 4,500 years ago, is part of Egypt's plan to welcome 
the new millennium and attract visitors. The restoration, which 
took nearly a year, cost $29,500, a government archaeologist said 
Sunday. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell slightly in midday trading  
Monday. The Nikkei fell 13.40 points to 15,959.28 early. On Friday, 
the average shed 204.51 points. 

</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya-Trinidad Fight On  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The monetary dispute in the camp of  
IBF champion Felix ``Tito'' Trinidad was resolved Sunday, giving 
the green light to the Sept. 18 date for a welterweight unification 
with WBC champion Oscar De La Hoya. Trinidad is a little-known 
fighter from Puerto Rico with an impressive 35-0 record that he 
upheld Saturday night with his 30th knockout, this one of 
Colombia's Hugo Pineda on Saturday night. De La Hoya is 31-0 with 
22 knockouts and will earn $15 million from the Sept. 18 fight at 
Mandalay Bay Hotel in Las Vegas. 

</P>
<P>
	Jeff Burton Wins Coca-Cola 600  
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Equally strong before the sun went down and  
after darkness descended, Jeff Burton powered his way to victory in 
the Coca-Cola 600 Sunday night at Lowe's Motor Speedway at 
Charlotte. Winning for the third time this year and the eighth in 
his career, Burton wound up about 10 car-lengths ahead of Bobby 
Labonte. Mark Martin was third and Tony Stewart fourth, 
successfully completing his odyssey of driving the Indianapolis 500 
and the Coca-Cola 600 on the same day. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
