<HEADLINE> Occidental Leaving Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) -- The Occidental Petroleum Corporation is  
pulling out of Bangladesh, handing over its oil and gas operations 
there to another U.S. company, an official said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-based Unocal Corporation will take over all  
Occidental's assets and liabilities in Bangladesh starting next 
month under a deal signed Thursday, said Terry Budden, Unocal's 
country representative. 
</P>
<P>
	Unocal's present investment of $260 million in Bangladesh could  
reach $1 billion if all planned projects, including power plants 
and gas pipelines, come through, Budden told journalists in the 
capital, Dhaka. 
</P>
<P>
	Occidental's General Manager Nigel Hopkinson said his company  
was withdrawing from Bangladesh after four years in order to 
concentrate in regions where it is already strong, including the 
Middle East and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will take over Unocal's holdings in Yemen.  
</P>
<P>
	Occidental's assets in Bangladesh include three gas blocks in  
the northeast in which Unocal already holds 50 percent working 
interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Unocal is also working in Myanmar, Indonesia, the Philippines,  
Thailand and Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
