<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Slowdown May Be Positive / Ticker Talk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The stock market has been looking a little  
sickly of late, but analysts say that is actually healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	They contend that the recent setbacks suffered by the great bull  
market stand to prolong its life by slowing down its pulse and 
cooling its temperature. 
</P>
<P>
	All the market averages have retreated of late from the new  
highs they reached earlier in the spring. The red-hot Internet 
stocks took a tumble. 
</P>
<P>
	On the economic front, fears of inflation have revived, and the  
Federal Reserve has signaled its willingness to tighten credit 
conditions if it sees fit. But analysts at Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. 
label all this ``a healthy consolidation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We view the market's essentially sideways movement over the  
past several weeks as beneficial,'' they say in the current edition 
of the firm's weekly advisory The Outlook. ``A digestive phase such 
as we are now witnessing is clearly in order. 
</P>
<P>
	``It helps avoid a damaging blowoff and gives earnings time to  
narrow the gap with stock prices at least somewhat. We don't see 
signs that the underlying upward trend is about to reverse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet stocks, in particular, are widely considered a case  
of glaring excess that may need a lot more correcting than has 
already occurred. Still, in the eyes of many analysts, their sharp 
drop from mid-April through May served as a caution to 
overenthusiastic speculators. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise, many observers believe the shock of a  
larger-than-expected 0.7 percent rise in the consumer price index 
for April, and a tilt toward Fed tightening, may work in the 
market's favor as time passes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Federal Open Market Committee has begun to set the stage  
for a rate hike,'' say Robert DiClemente and Mitchell Held, 
economists at Salomon Smith Barney. ``Despite near-term risks, such 
a tack would prolong the expansion, cap an incipient inflation 
threat, and underpin long-term investments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say that if the Fed raises short-term interest rates,  
rates in the long-term bond market could actually fall, reflecting 
encouragement among bond traders that the central bank was staying 
vigilant against inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides, some market-watchers add, a touch of inflation now may  
be far less troublesome than the specter of deflation that loomed 
over the markets at the worst of the Asian financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``It now seems very likely that the cyclical low in both  
producer and consumer prices has been seen,'' says Peter Canelo, an 
investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	``Higher inflation and higher interest rates are bad news for  
high-P-E growth stocks. However, the shift in inflationary 
expectations corresponds with a more-vigorous U.S. economy and 
stronger earnings growth. 'Global healing' has resulted in rising 
U.S. export orders in the past three months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amid all these pluses and minuses, many observers say there is a  
good chance the economy and the markets can maintain the favorable 
balance they have enjoyed for the past several years. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, they say, a hint from the Fed that it is willing  
to tighten credit oftentimes lately has served the purpose that 
used to require overt action to raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``A tightening bias does not equate to a tightening,'' says Jack  
Lavery, economic consultant to Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``The Fed has 
had a tightening bias on 15 separate occasions since 1996 and has, 
in fact, raised interest rates only once.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As S&AMP;P's Outlook commented recently, ``It has been a mistake to  
underestimate this market's ability to climb a wall of worry.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
