<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990530.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 11:01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Enjoy Crusty Bread </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RHINEBECK, N.Y. (AP) -- Consider the lowly loaf of bread -- soft  
and spongy, white and sliced. 
</P>
<P>
	Now consider the display at Bread Alone.  
</P>
<P>
	There are crusty brown baguettes and boules emitting  
earthy-sweet aromas. There are fresh-baked loaves dusted with 
flour, many with names to match their exotic ingredients: sesame 
semolina, rustic corn, whole wheat walnut, onion levain and organic 
sourdough miche. 
</P>
<P>
	And there are customers, lots of them.  
</P>
<P>
	``This business will grow as fast as I want it to grow,'' said  
Dan Leader as he sat in his newest Bread Alone store, an eat-in 
Hudson Valley shop with the air of a funky cappucino joint. 
</P>
<P>
	Leader is benefitting from a bullish bread market. Sales of  
fresher, crustier ``specialty breads'' are rising in the United 
States as the country that perfected the packaged, pre-sliced loaf 
acquires more discriminating tastes. 
</P>
<P>
	The small but tight-knit fraternity of bakers -- buoyed by an  
unprecedented American win in an international baking competition 
this year -- even see signs of a bread Renaissance. 
</P>
<P>
	The term ``specialty bread'' defines any number of hearth-baked  
crusty creations, from long, thin baguettes to rounded boules. A 
premium is put on freshness and sometimes unusual ingredients: 
shallots, chocolate, dried cherries, kalamata olives, Asiago cheese 
-- even hot peppers. 
</P>
<P>
	Artisan breads -- like the ones Leader produces -- are a subset of  
specialty breads. Kneading and shaping is done as much as possible 
by hand. Longer fermentation times give the bread a richer, 
earthier taste. 
</P>
<P>
	Artisans -- who are not always charitable toward the larger  
specialty market -- tend to be passionate about their craft. They 
will describe the perfect loaf in almost blushingly sensual detail: 
The outside gives a springy resistance to the touch; crusts crackle 
to the bite; sinewy dough yields a sweet, sharp hint of 
fermentation. 
</P>
<P>
	While the taste is tops, the cost can be too. Prices of $3 to $5  
are common for fancy breads. 
</P>
<P>
	Such high-end breads have had an established niche since at  
least the mid-'80's, but their popularity is growing. Ed Lee, 
editor of the trade publication Modern Baking magazine, said the 
market for specialty breads has been growing for about five years 
as more people are introduced to exotic bread. 
</P>
<P>
	``People say: `Whoa! This stuff tastes pretty good,''' Lee said.  
``And they're willing to pay for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Specialty breads are even making headway in the South,  
traditional ``white bread territory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta-area wholesaler Richard Orta admitted that peddling  
crustier breads was a ``hard sell'' when he started his BreadWorks 
business last year. He recalls potential customers at a country 
club saying ``This is great stuff Richard, but do you have it in 
soft?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Orta mixed in artisan rolls with the soft rolls, and the country  
clubbers soon developed heartier tastes. Others did too -- Orta has 
about 70 accounts with local businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Mistell, head of the Bread Bakers Guild of America, said a  
``bread culture'' has grown recently, evidenced by things such as 
newspaper food critics reviewing new bread bakeries. Mistell said 
bread is taken especially seriously in New York City, San 
Francisco, Seattle and his hometown, Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a far cry from 15 years ago, when Leader said people  
considered him crazy for opening his Bread Alone bakery in the 
remote Catskill town of Boiceville. Today, the bakery supplies 
three stores. There are two more Bread Alone shops in Austin, 
Texas, and one set to open in June in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Leader sees the growth as part of the broader trend of Americans  
developing tastes for all sorts of better foods, like wines, 
cheeses and coffees. In fact, the boom of high-end coffee shops has 
tended to carry fine bakery goods in its wake. A chewy bite of 
baguette washes down well with espresso, it seems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans are waking up to what good food can be,'' Leader  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another reason for bakers to hold their hats a little higher  
came in February. That was when Thomas Gumpel and Robert Jorin of 
the Culinary Institute of America in St. Helena, Calif., and Jan 
Schat of the Academia del Fornaio baking school of Burlingame, 
Calif., took top-prize honors in the World Cup of Baking. 
</P>
<P>
	The contest is hardly a household word, but hopes are high that  
the win will give added attention to artisan baking. It has already 
bought mainstream press attention, including a People magazine 
spread with a picture of the beaming bakers, baguettes in hand. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gumpel, for one, fears that corporate bakers trying to  
capitalize on the popularity of specialty breads will blur the 
distinctions between artisan and other breads. He noted that one 
supermarket chain is putting its machine-made loaves in a fancy new 
bag with wheat stalks on it and calling it artisan bread. 
</P>
<P>
	Other bakers worry about increasing competition, especially from  
partially baked, frozen loaves of specialty bread, which are 
finished up in-house. They have started showing up in more 
supermarkets and trendy, upscale restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	La Brea Bakery of Los Angeles, for instance, distributes its  
frozen loaves in several states, including Arizona, California, 
Colorado, Florida, Hawaii, Nevada and Wisconsin. The bread has 
gotten rave reviews from food critics and chefs. 
</P>
<P>
	But Leader said there's no reason for concern. With the bread  
market estimated to exceed $15 billion a year, he said that there's 
plenty of room for competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the artisan bread market took 2 percent of the total  
market,'' Leader said, ``well, we'd all be working seven days a 
week, 24 hours a day.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
