<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Burns Leads Australia in Cycling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRISCO, Texas (AP) -- Australian Alayna Burns recovered from a  
fall during the women's points race to finish in second, but led 
her mates to the team title Sunday in the World Cup of Track 
Cycling. 
</P>
<P>
	Burns was among a half-dozen riders who crashed the 41st of the  
80-lap race. Three riders were injured, but Burns returned to the 
competition with some scrapes to finish second. 
</P>
<P>
	She also earned 10 points toward the team competition. Australia  
registered 83 team points to win the team crown, followed closely 
by the United States and France, who both compiled 81 points. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. cyclists Karen Dunne and Erin Veenstra were finished fourth  
and fifth, respectively in the points race. 
</P>
<P>
	Laurent Gane of France won his second medal of the three-day  
event with a victory in the Keirin, an eight-lap race, which is 
paced for the first half with a motorized bicycle. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Gane defeated American Marty Nothstein to take the  
match sprint title. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
