<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Netanyahu Confirms Talks With Syria  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Benjamin Netanyahu acknowledged conducting  
secret talks with Syria that included a proposal to replace Israeli 
soldiers on the Golan Heights with foreign troops, a Cabinet 
minister said today. Netanyahu, trounced by moderate Ehud Barak in 
elections two weeks ago, outwardly maintained an unwavering 
commitment to Israeli sovereignty over the strategic plateau, 
captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast war. But reports last week 
said that the outgoing prime minister talked with Syria for a year 
and nearly reached agreements for substantial withdrawals. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Already Facing Trouble  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel's prime minister-elect Ehud Barak came  
under mounting pressure today to take a stand on the future of 
Jewish settlements in lands that both Jews and Arabs claim. 
Palestinians want Barak to stop settlement activity now. His 
preferred coalition partner -- the hard-line Likud party he ousted -- 
wants guarantees that some settlement growth will continue. The 
demands were a switch from the days after Barak's win, when 
Palestinians warmly welcomed his victory and Likud members praised 
him for extending his hand. A spokesman said today that Barak would 
not intervene until he takes power. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Confirms Bridge Attack  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO acknowledged attacking a bridge  
in central Serbia today, saying the span was a legitimate and 
designated target. The alliance did not confirm Yugoslav media 
reports of 11 deaths in the attack. The Tanjug news agency reported 
that several cars plunged into the Velika Morava River after three 
missiles struck the bridge near the town of Krusevac. The news 
agency said the attack wounded 40 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Western Journalists Hurt in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A NATO missile attack in Kosovo hit  
near a convoy of Western journalists today, killing a driver and 
wounding a Times of London reporter and two others, the Serb-run 
Media Center in Pristina said. A NATO spokesman said he was unable 
to comment. The extent of the injuries was not immediately clear, 
but the center said the wounded were taken to the Prizren hospital. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Espionage Could Cost Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson urged an end  
to ``scapegoating'' in the Chinese espionage scandal and said today 
he would fire department officials for failing to act on signs 
China was stealing nuclear secrets. Richardson said dismissals and 
demotions could come as early as this week, after he receives a 
report on security lapses at the Los Alamos lab that may have 
contributed to China's thefts. He also urged a renewed focus on 
increased security. 

</P>
<P>
	Car Haulers Strike Looms  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- The Teamsters and new car haulers were  
still far apart today on major issues such as pay for new workers 
and pensions as a strike deadline loomed. Teamsters President James 
P. Hoffa said the union was ready to strike when its contract 
expires at 12:01 a.m. EDT Tuesday. Negotiations began in February 
between the Teamsters, representing 12,800 workers in the contract 
dispute, and the National Automobile Transporters Association, 
which is made up of 17 companies. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Refugee Wins Beauty Contest  
</P>
<P>
	TIRANA, Albania (AP) -- A 19-year-old student from neighboring  
Kosovo, one of more than 840,000 ethnic Albanians forced out of the 
province, has been crowned Miss Albania '99. Venera Mustafa, who 
won late last night, said her greatest desire is to return to 
Kosovo as soon as possible. Her hometown is the provincial capital, 
Pristina. Ms. Mustafa will represent Albania in a Miss Europe 
contest in about a month. 

</P>
<P>
	Avalanche Lead Stars Series 3-2  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Chris Drury scored his second straight game-winner  
and fourth of the playoffs as the Colorado Avalanche beat the 
Dallas Stars 7-5 today in an unlikely wide-open game and moved one 
victory away from the Stanley Cup finals. The Avalanche, who blew a 
two-goal lead late in the game before coming back to win, took a 
3-2 lead in their best-of-7 Western Conference finals. They can 
advance to the championship round with a victory in Game 6 Tuesday 
night in Denver. 

</P>
<P>
	Diamondbacks Beat Mets 10-1  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Randy Johnson shut down the New York Mets with  
his powerful left arm and knocked out Masato Yoshii with his 
usually weak bat. Johnson struck out 10 in eight dominating innings 
and had two hits and an RBI to lead the Arizona Diamondbacks to 
their sixth straight win, 10-1 over the New York Mets today. Steve 
Finley went 4-for-5 with two home runs, a three-run shot in the 
first and a two-run shot in the third, as Arizona swept the 
three-game series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
