<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	German Pols Say No to Ground Troops  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Government and opposition politicians  
reiterated today that Germany will not provide ground troops for a 
possible invasion of Kosovo, while at the same time backing an 
international peacekeeping force in the region once the fighting 
stops. Meanwhile, NATO war planes struck at targets across Serbia 
today in intensified attacks meant to force President Slobodan 
Milosevic to accept alliance demands on Kosovo. NATO spokesman 
Jamie Shea today said the Yugoslav leader is slowly moving from a 
position ``of almost total defiance of the international 
community'' but still far away from accepting NATO conditions for 
ending the air campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	Mandela Campaigns for Successor  
</P>
<P>
	SOWETO, South Africa (AP) -- Nelson Mandela took the stage today  
at what will likely be his last mass rally as president and told 
cheering supporters that South Africa's struggle to recover from 
apartheid continues. Nearly 80,000 people packed into a 
Johannesburg soccer stadium to hear Mandela speak three days before 
South Africans elect their second post-apartheid government. 
Mandela and his heir apparent, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, were 
greeted with thunderous chants as they entered the stadium on a 
golf cart and circled the field. 

</P>
<P>
	China Accuses U.S. on Tiananmen  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Critical resolutions in the U.S. Congress marking  
the 10th anniversary of the Tiananmen Square democracy 
demonstrations were meant to destabilize China and harm bilateral 
relations, a Chinese legislative official declared today. Friday is 
the anniversary of the military assault that killed hundreds. 
Today's statement accused U.S. lawmakers of ``wantonly distorting 
historical facts,'' stirring up anti-China sentiment and 
obstructing U.S.-China relations, the state-run Xinhua News Agency 
reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Astronauts Complete Long Spacewalk  
</P>
<P>
	SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) -- Discovery's astronauts attached  
cranes and other tools to the outside of the international space 
station today during an exceptionally long spacewalk, then turned 
to the bigger work inside. The crew plans to enter the space 
station tonight for 3 1/2 days of deliveries and repairs. Tamara 
Jernigan and Dr. Daniel Barry spent eight hours outside the 
orbiting complex -- almost a spacewalk record. The shuttle is due 
back June 6. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Vacation Spending Rising  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Almost one-quarter of those surveyed in an  
Associated Press poll conducted by ICR of Media, Pa., say they 
expect to spend more on getaways than they did a year ago. The 
strong economy is a big factor. About six out of 10 say they expect 
to spend as much on vacations in 1999 as in 1998. The typical 
American likes to vacation in the summer, travel by car and spend a 
week or less on the trip, according to the poll. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Railroads To Take Over Conrail  
</P>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- Two railroads this week will take over and  
carve up what once was the government-run Conrail, continuing a 
trend toward consolidation in an industry struggling to compete 
with truckers. Beginning Tuesday, shippers, regulators and other 
railroads will watch closely as CSX and Norfolk Southern attempt to 
redraw the rail map while avoiding the service foul-up that 
followed the last major rail merger. To pay Conrail's $10.3 billion 
purchase price, both CSX and Norfolk Southern are counting on 
persuading more shippers to carry goods by rail. 

</P>
<P>
	Williams, Capriati Out at French Open  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Fifth-seeded Venus Williams made a surprise exit  
from the French Open today, blowing three match points and losing 
2-6, 7-6 (9-7), 6-3 to Austrian qualifier Barbara Schwartz, ranked 
125th in the world. Also eliminated was Jennifer Capriati, her 
comeback ending with a 6-2, 6-3 loss to No. 2-seeded Lindsay 
Davenport. Moving on to the quarterfinals are top-seeded Martina 
Hingis, defending champion Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario, Steffi Graf and 
Monica Seles. 

</P>
<P>
	Indy Crew Chief Hit by Car  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A race car leaving a pit stop struck and  
critically injured a crew member at the Indianapolis 500 today. 
Steve Fried, the chief mechanic and right front man for Robbie 
McGehee, was directing the car out of the pit when he was struck 
from behind by Jimmy Kite's car. He flipped into the air, landed on 
his face and was bleeding badly as he was taken to Methodist 
Hospital, where he is listed in ``very critical'' condition. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  

</P>
