<DOCNO> APW19990530.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 23:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspected Nazi Helper Won't Testify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A man who lived in the United States for  
nearly three decades has returned to Lithuania rather than testify 
about his activities as a policeman in his Nazi-occupied homeland 
during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight by Aloyzas Balsys, 86, to stay in the United States  
without testifying resulted last year in a landmark Supreme Court 
decision that fear of prosecution abroad is insufficient ground to 
invoke the Fifth Amendment's protection from self-incrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department said Sunday that Balsys, formerly of New  
York City, left Saturday, a day ahead of a departure deadline set 
in a settlement with the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Balsys' problems began with a Justice subpoena that required his  
testimony on his wartime conduct in Vilnius, the Lithuanian 
capital. He contended the answers would open him up to prosecution 
in Lithuania, Israel or Germany and he refused to testify, invoking 
his Fifth Amendment rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court agreed with the federal trial judge's ruling  
that Balsys could not refuse to testify and it overturned an 
appeals court decision that the Fifth Amendment protected Balsys. 
</P>
<P>
	``In light of the Supreme Court's decision, Balsys agreed to  
depart the United States permanently for Lithuania in order to 
avoid enforcement of the subpoena,'' a Justice Department statement 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the settlement, ``Balsys conceded that he misrepresented  
and concealed his true wartime activities when he entered the 
United States,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Balsys arrived in the United States in 1961 from England and  
never took U.S. citizenship. He told U.S. immigration officials on 
his arrival that he served in the Lithuanian army from 1934 to 
1940, then lived in hiding in that Baltic country until 1944. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli M. Rosenbaum, director of the Justice Department's Office of  
Special Investigations, said historians on his staff had found 
documents showing that Balsys served with the Nazi-sponsored 
Lithuanian Security Police, the Saugumas, at least until 1943. 
</P>
<P>
	He headed a Saugumas precinct office in Vilnius, Lithuania's  
capital. The Lithuanians acted as Gestapo surrogates, Rosenbaum 
said, and turned over to the Nazis Jews and Lithuanians who helped 
them. The Justice Department said nearly 55,000 of Vilnius' 60,000 
Jews were summarily executed at Panerjai, a wooded area near the 
capital, during the Nazi occupation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court's ruling in the Balsys case was cited by a  
federal judge in Florida in a case involving a Lithuanian found in 
contempt of court. 
</P>
<P>
	Vytautas Gecas, 77, of Sunny Hills, Fla., was ordered to jail  
three weeks ago for refusing to testify about his wartime 
activities in his homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	On the same day the Supreme Court ruled against Balsys, it  
refused to hear Gecas' appeal of an order to testify despite 
fearing prosecution in Lithuania, Israel or Germany. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990530.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 17:02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> One Race Down, One To Go for Stewart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- While the other 32 drivers in the  
Indianapolis 500 rested and relaxed after the checkered flag fell 
today, Tony Stewart rushed to the airport, changed into another 
racing suit, took a quick nap and got ready to do it all over 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	And then some.  
</P>
<P>
	Stewart still had 600 miles and 1,600 mind-numbing left turns,  
to go. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to become the first driver to complete the Indianapolis  
500 and the Coca-Cola 600 on the same day, Stewart accomplished the 
first part with no problem. 
</P>
<P>
	He finished ninth, four laps behind winner Kenny Brack, on a day  
when several of the top racers were knocked out by crashes and 
engine blowouts. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't exactly the easiest of races. After starting in the  
eighth row, Stewart had handling problems with his car for much of 
the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``In all honesty, I'm not as disappointed as I thought I would  
be,'' Stewart said on the private jet that took him to North 
Carolina for the second half of his racing doubleheader. ``The guys 
worked really hard and built me a great car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After crossing the finish line at Indy, Stewart sprinted to his  
trailer, changed into a red T-shirt and blue jeans and returned to 
his garage to say goodbye to his crew. They waved and cheered as 
Stewart was whisked away in a golf cart to a helicopter, waiting on 
the infield near the third turn. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a three-minute ride to the Indianapolis airport, where  
The Home Depot, his sponsor, had its private jet waiting for the 
65-minute flight to North Carolina. After that, Stewart had another 
helicopter ride to Lowe's Motor Speedway, where he was supposed to 
start in the 27th spot in the Coca-Cola. Since he missed the 
driver's meeting, however, he was sent to the back of the grid and 
started in the 43rd spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Aboard the plane, Stewart changed into his NASCAR racing suit,  
ate a Power Bar and sipped Powerade and water. Contrary to what 
doctors expected, he didn't need any intravenous fluids. He had a 
blister on his right hand from the steering wheel, another blister 
on his right knee from the steering column and was a little tired. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's to be expected after a 500-mile race,'' Stewart said  
before dozing off for a quick nap on a sofa in the back of the jet. 
``I'm really excited, though. I thought I'd feel a lot more 
fatigued. I think after an hour's sleep, I'll be fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the plane landed in the track infield, Stewart wiped the  
sleep from his eyes, put on his driving shoes and got ready for 
another plane ride, this time on a helicopter borrowed from fellow 
NASCAR driver Rusty Wallace. 
</P>
<P>
	As the helicopter flew low around the speedway, fans stood,  
cheered and waved. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's awesome,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	When the helicopter landed, Stewart got into a white Camaro and  
was driven around the track as part of driver introductions. 
</P>
<P>
	After three years in the Indy Racing league, Stewart switched to  
NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit and has done better than anyone 
expected. He's had five top-10 finishes in his first 11 races, and 
captured his first pole. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 28-year-old Indiana native didn't want to give up his  
chance to win at Indy -- even if it meant driving 1,100 miles in 
less than 12 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``A beautiful sunny day like this, I suppose people could figure  
out better things to do,'' he said. ``But I'm looking forward to 
doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Andretti was the first to do the double in 1994, but he  
crashed in the Coca-Cola 600 and didn't finish the race. Robby 
Gordon's attempt in 1997 was rained out in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the long day, Stewart looked loose and relaxed Sunday  
morning. When he walked to his race car, his crew handed him two 
helmets and told him to pick one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eenie, meenie, minie, mo,'' Stewart said as his crew laughed.  
</P>
<P>
	Stewart has been shuttling back and forth between Indy and  
Concord the past two weeks, and he arrived in Indianapolis late 
Saturday after two days of practice in North Carolina. After 
sleeping in his motor coach at the speedway, Stewart and fiancee 
Krista Dwyer arrived at his garage about 9:25 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	As he walked onto the track, there were loud cheers from the  
crowd. People dashed in front of Stewart to get pictures, and 
several drivers stopped to wish him luck. His father, Nelson, gave 
his son a bear hug and told him to have a good day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last two weeks have been the most relaxing months of May  
I've had,'' said Stewart, co-owner of his Indy team. ``We did it 
our way. We didn't have to answer to anyone else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The handling problems in his Indy car were caused by a mistake  
in the pits. While working on the Dallara Oldsmobile Aurora, the 
crew released the jack too soon and slightly damaged the car. 
</P>
<P>
	``After that, you're in a survival mode,'' crew chief Larry  
Curry said. ``You just want to get the car home. I'm disappointed 
in the fact we made that mistake. We would have been the fourth or 
fifth or sixth car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team also was hurt by the lack of practice time, since  
Stewart also had to focus on his Winston Cup team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to win the race, but we did everything we could do,''  
he said before hinting this won't be the last time he does double 
duty. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a lesson for next year.''  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990530.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 07:01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Viagra Stolen From Manila Drugstore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- About 10 men armed with rifles broke  
into a drugstore in a Manila suburb Sunday and stole boxes of the 
anti-impotence drug Viagra and cash, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The thieves fired at a police patrol car as they emerged from  
the Mercury Drugstore in Quezon City, police said. A woman 
bystander was shot in the arm, and the thieves fled in two cars and 
a van. 
</P>
<P>
	Viagra was the only medicine taken by the robbers, who seemed to  
know where it was stored, said an official from the Mercury chain. 
Store employees were still determining how much was taken, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the pre-dawn robbery, the gang also forced a drugstore  
supervisor to open a vault from which a large amount of cash was 
apparently taken, the official said on condition on anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The supervisor and a few other clerks had stayed in the  
drugstore overnight for an inventory, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Viagra was introduced last October in the Philippines. Although  
the drug's introduction was widely welcomed, many Filipinos say 
they cannot afford its high price. 
</P>
<P>
	Filipinos have generally relied on traditional balms, herbs,  
homemade concoctions and Chinese traditional medicine to deal with 
impotence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990530.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 06:20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indian Strikes in Kashmir Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- As fighter jets pounded a Himalayan border  
expanse, Indian military columns inched closer to hide-outs of 
hundreds of Islamic guerrillas in Kashmir, officials and military 
commanders said. 
</P>
<P>
	India's prime minister won the backing of political rivals on  
the airstrikes and said he had rejected a suggestion by his 
Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz Sharif, to end the military action in 
the divided territory, claimed by both of the nuclear nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not stop until our aim is achieved,'' Press Trust of  
India quoted Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee as telling a 
meeting of major political parties. 
</P>
<P>
	The air force began sorties Wednesday aimed at infiltrators  
entrenched in Indian territory in Kashmir. New Delhi says they 
include Afghan mercenaries and Pakistan army soldiers disguised as 
guerrillas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stopping the airstrikes may not be possible. It cannot be  
one-sided,'' Vajpayee said he had told the Pakistani prime minister 
in a telephone call Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In their call, Sharif offered to send his foreign minister to  
New Delhi for talks to defuse the tension. But India has not yet 
given its formal consent for the visit, and demanded that Pakistan 
stop its military from dispatching infiltrators to Kashmir as it 
considered Sharif's offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Kashmir has been at the center of two of the three wars that  
India and Pakistan have fought since their independence in 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, Russia and other countries have urged  
restraint, fearing Kashmir could spark a new all-out war between 
the two nations, which both exploded nuclear devices in underground 
tests last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan has denied any connection to the guerrillas and has  
accused India of hitting its territory in the airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian army spokesman Maj. Gen. J.J. Singh said strikes by MiGs  
and helicopter gunships had helped drive out many guerrillas. But 
ground fighting could last for several weeks before the military 
regained control over the area, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of miles north of New Delhi, along the unofficial  
border through Kashmir both nations agreed to after the last war, 
Indian army soldiers made their way up to positions held by the 
guerrillas at about 17,000 feet, a military commander said on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The soldiers closed in within about 200 yards of the  
infiltrators and in some places even within 50 yards, expecting a 
hand-to-hand fight and the possibility of heavy casualties, the 
commander said. 
</P>
<P>
	In earlier close-quarter fighting, Indian soldiers took some  
positions on the slopes of the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Artillery battles also raged through the night. The military  
camp at Dras, close to the disputed border, came under heavy fire. 
But there was no damage or casualties, the commander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Minister George Fernandes, in New Delhi, said that some  
400 infiltrators had so far been killed in the operation and that 
others had been captured. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian army said its casualties stand at 29 killed and 128  
wounded. Twelve soldiers or officers are missing, the army said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. built F-16 fighter jet of the Pakistan Air Force crossed  
about 3,000 yards into Indian air space and was fired at by an 
Indian anti-aircraft gun, a local commander said on condition of 
anonymity. The intrusion occurred near Pandrass, a town near the 
Line of Control, the commander said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane dived and fired at the gun, turning back without  
causing any damage, the commander said. 
</P>
<P>
	But an air force spokesman in New Delhi denied any such  
incident. Pakistani army spokesman Brig. Rashid Quereshi also said 
the report didn't seem correct. He would not say whether Pakistan 
has deployed F-16s in the conflict zone, saying military strategy 
and tactics were confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	Early Friday, an Indian MI-17 helicopter gunship was downed and  
its four-member crew was killed. The United Jehad Council, an 
umbrella group of Kashmiri Islamic militant groups, claimed 
responsibility. India lost two MiG fighter jets Thursday, one to 
Pakistani anti-aircraft guns and the other due to a mechanical 
failure. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the two pilots died after his plane crashed in Pakistani  
territory. The other pilot was taken prisoner in Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990530.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 06:20:29 </DATE_TIME>
