<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crew Chief Hit by Car Leaving Pit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A race car leaving a pit stop struck and  
critically injured a crew member at the Indianapolis 500 on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Fried, the chief mechanic and right front tire man for  
Robbie McGehee, was directing the car out of the pit when he was 
hit from behind by Jimmy Kite's car. 
</P>
<P>
	He flipped into the air, landed on his face and was bleeding  
badly as he was taken to Methodist Hospital, where he was listed in 
critical condition, but responding to stimulation. Linda Conti, the 
team manager, went to the hospital with Fried. 
</P>
<P>
	No crew member has been killed at Indy since 1973, when Armando  
Tehran, a mechanic for driver Swede Savage, was struck by a fire 
truck speeding from the pits to the scene of a crash that fatally 
injured Savage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fried accident was triggered when Kite, the youngest driver  
in the race at 23, was hit by Johnny Unser, whose brakes failed as 
he was entering the pit. 
</P>
<P>
	Kite's steering broke and his car lurched into Fried.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was on the brakes as hard as I could. There's nothing you  
could do with broken steering,'' Kite said. ``I feel bad right now. 
There's nothing you could do. It's the most helpless feeling I've 
ever had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGehee stayed in the race and was running in the top 10, on the  
lead lap, at the halfway point. 
</P>
<P>
	Another pit accident later in the race knocked out Greg Ray, who  
had just inherited the lead when Arie Luyendyk crashed in the third 
turn. Ray dashed into the pits for a quick refueling but ran into 
Mark Dismore. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray took off his steering wheel and slammed it on top of his  
car. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just makes you want to cry,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
