<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Banks To Pay Fee for Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's banks will have to pay 0.4 percent  
of their total deposits for coverage from Mexico's new deposit 
insurance agency, the agency, known as IPAB, announced Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 0.4 percent required by IPAB is the minimum allowed by the  
Bank Savings' Protection Law passed in Congress last December, 
which created IPAB to launch a new regulatory framework for 
Mexico's banking system. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is important the banks channel an important part of their  
income to building reserves and fortifying their financial 
position,'' IPAB said in explaining why banks would have to pay the 
minimum possible fee for deposit insurance coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	IPAB, however, reserved the right to raise the fees to no more  
than 0.5 percent ``in case conditions arise requiring an increase 
in quotas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In ``extraordinary circumstances,'' the fees paid by individual  
banks will be reduced to no more than 0.3 percent, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	IPAB also announced a seven-stage calendar for gradually  
reducing deposit insurance coverage to 400,000 inflation-linked 
accounting units known as UDI's worth around $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, banks were given unlimited deposit insurance  
coverage. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
