<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 11:41:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Bush To Crow About Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush awaited  
legislative approval of tax cuts worth about $1.7 billion, less 
than he sought but enough to claim bragging rights in a 
presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	While the final plan was almost $1 billion less than Bush wanted  
-- and about one-fourth the $6.4 billion budget surplus lawmakers 
had to work with -- the Republican governor still was on the verge 
of claiming a big tax cut. Lawmakers were finishing their work by 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He asked for $2.6 billion in various cuts and was taking less:  
some $1.2 billion in property tax relief, plus $506 million in 
sales and business tax breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a Republican primary, taxes are a great issue. It'll kill  
you or make you. He's golden on taxes,'' said Bill Miller, a Texas 
political consultant who has worked for Democrats and Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got bragging rights,'' Miller said. ``He's got real  
thrust for his presidential campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said Bush ducked difficult issues and left it to  
lawmakers to hammer out everything from teacher pay to children's 
health insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to sit on the fence about everything there is and see  
which way the wind's blowing,'' said Texas Democratic Party chair 
Molly Beth Malcolm. ``A leader takes a stand on tough issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other issues that will be scrutinized as Bush begins to sound  
out a presidential effort in the coming weeks: 
</P>
<P>
	--Democrats and Republicans approved his proposals to require  
parental notification before minors can get an abortion, jail 
juveniles caught with guns and begin deregulation of the electric 
utility industry. 
</P>
<P>
	--His biggest defeat was failure to get taxpayer-funded vouchers  
to pay private school tuition. His brother, Gov. Jeb Bush, has 
approval for vouchers in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	--Critics beat up the Texas governor over the Legislature's  
refusal to toughen the state hate crimes law or require background 
checks on buyers at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush sat out those fights. He said ``all crime is hate'' but  
left the debate to lawmakers; he said he favored background checks 
but called it a federal matter. 
</P>
<P>
	While he took heat, the death of those bills in legislative  
committees kept Bush from having to sign or veto them. That spared 
him the possible wrath of voters on either side of two politically 
contentious issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``I call him Governor beat-around-the-Bush,'' Mrs. Malcolm said.  
``It's rhetoric vs. reality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Time and again, Democrats accused Bush of putting his  
presidential ambitions first. 
</P>
<P>
	They accused him of putting too much emphasis on corporate tax  
relief; pushing property tax cuts that benefit only some Texans 
rather than broad sales tax cuts for all; failing to demand 
stronger environmental measures; and being stingy toward the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're either going to care more about the voters in New  
Hampshire or Iowa, or we're going to care more about the school 
children of Texas,'' Rep. Domingo Garcia of Dallas complained 
during a debate pitting property tax cuts against funding for 
smaller school classes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
