<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Firings Expected in China Spy Case  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said today  
that demotions and dismissals could come as early as this week for 
department officials who failed to act on signs China was stealing 
secrets from a U.S. nuclear weapons lab. He said he is waiting for 
an internal report on security lapses at the Los Alamos lab in New 
Mexico that may have contributed to China's thefts. Richardson 
stressed today that Energy counterintelligence has implemented 85 
percent of the measures recommended by a congressional report to 
stop espionage attempts. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs Claim 11 Killed in Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO missiles slammed into a bridge  
crowded with market-goers and cars in central Serbia today, killing 
11 people, state-run media said. Several cars plunged into the 
Velika Morava River after three missiles struck the bridge, Tanjug 
news agency reported. Divers were searching for victims, said the 
news agency, adding that the attack wounded 40 people, including 
five in critical condition. There was no immediate NATO 
confirmation of the report. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Force May Help Rebuild Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The 50,000 peacekeepers NATO plans for Kosovo  
after the bombing ends would include heavily armed soldiers to 
protect returning refugees and hard-hat engineers to rebuild roads, 
airports and utilities battered by the allies. The peacekeeping 
force is only a theoretical army, for now, with no timetable to 
stop the airstrikes against the forces of Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic. That has not prevented the allies from planning 
the force's makeup and duties. The peacekeepers would include 
engineers, road crews, mine-clearing teams, water purification 
experts and police troops. 

</P>
<P>
	Mandela: Back My Successor  
</P>
<P>
	SOWETO, South Africa (AP) -- Nelson Mandela told cheering  
supporters today that South Africa's struggle to recover from 
apartheid continues. Nearly 80,000 people packed into a 
Johannesburg stadium to hear Mandela speak three days before South 
Africans elect their second post-apartheid government. Mandela told 
the crowd they had struck a ``death blow'' to apartheid when they 
overwhelmingly elected the ANC five years ago. Surveys predict the 
ANC will win at least 60 percent of the vote Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Dozens Die in Cholera Outbreak  
</P>
<P>
	BANLUNG, Cambodia (AP) -- A cholera outbreak in northeast  
Cambodia has killed at least 96 people and infected 1,538 since 
late April, aid agencies and hospital staff have reported. At least 
89 people have died in the sparsely populated Ratanakiri province, 
and seven other deaths were reported in neighboring Stung Treng 
province. The remoteness of the affected areas and the poor state 
of health care have frustrated health workers. 

</P>
<P>
	Astronauts Finish Lengthy Spacewalk  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Discovery's astronauts rigged cranes  
and other tools to the international space station today, then 
turned to the bigger work inside. The crew of seven planned to 
enter the space station tonight for three days of repairs. Among 
the jobs awaiting them: pulling up the floor to replace electrical 
meters on Russian batteries that aren't charging properly, trying 
to fix a broken U.S. communication system, and installing mufflers 
to reduce noise. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Vacation Spending Rising  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many Americans expect to spend more on  
vacations this year than they did last year, according to a poll. 
Almost one-quarter of those surveyed in an AP poll conducted by ICR 
of Media, Pa., say they expect to spend more on getaways than they 
did in 1998. The typical American vacations in the summer, travels 
by car and spends a week or less on the trip, according to the 
poll. 

</P>
<P>
	Kenny Brack Wins Indy 500  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Kenny Brack drove to Victory Lane, giving  
owner A.J. Foyt his fifth Indianapolis 500 victory and first as a 
car owner today. Brack took the lead just over one lap from the end 
when Robby Gordon lost his gamble and ran out of fuel. Gordon 
skipped a late pit stop and tried to go the final 32 laps on one 
tank of fuel, but his engine sputtered and died near the end of the 
199th lap of the 200-lap race. Foyt drivers Billy Boat and Robbie 
Buhl finished third and sixth, respectively. 

</P>
<P>
	One Down, One to Go for Stewart  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tony Stewart finished ninth today in the  
Indianapolis 500, but he still has 600 miles to go in his quest to 
become the first driver to complete the Indy 500 and the Coca-Cola 
600. Shortly after the race ended, he sprinted for a helicopter and 
headed for the airport to board a plane to North Carolina. It's a 
50-minute flight, and then he's got another helicopter ride to 
Lowe's Motor Speedway. He'll start in the 27th spot in the 
Coca-Cola. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
</TEXT>
