<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 11:31:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Control Plan Saved Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Malaysia's sudden decision to  
impose exchange control measures last year not only saved the 
country from disaster, but other nations in the region as well by 
scaring away currency speculators, a central bank official said 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after Malaysia introduced exchange control measures Sept.  
1, the economy of countries in the region started to recover, the 
adviser to the bank, Nor Mohamed Yakcop said in the Mingguan 
Malaysia newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	According to him, several months before Malaysia introduced  
exchange controls, there was a plan by hedge fund managers and 
other speculators to weaken further the ringgit to just 5 ringgit 
to the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	There were also plans for similar action against currencies of  
Thailand, Indonesia and Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar is now officially pegged to 4.80 ringgit.  
</P>
<P>
	``As such, it was vital to them that these three countries which  
did not impose exchange control measures received assistance from 
the International Monetary Fund,'' said Nor Mohammed. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysia had succeeded in its economic recovery on the  
initiative of the people themselves and ``we did not receive a cent 
from the IMF rescue fund of $180 billion,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
