<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russia Continues Work on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Seeking to map out a strategy to  
ending the Kosovo conflict, Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin met 
in Moscow today with Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and other top 
government officials. Chernomyrdin said after the talks that 
Yugoslavia's ``sovereignty and territorial integrity'' remained 
inviolable, meaning Russia still opposes a well-armed foreign force 
in Kosovo with a strong NATO component. NATO wants Yugoslavia to 
withdraw its troops from Kosovo and let 840,000 ethnic Albanian 
refugees who have fled or been expelled from the province to return 
under the protection of an international peacekeeping force. 
Yugoslavia refuses to agree to the peacekeeping force. 

</P>
<P>
	Astronauts Enter Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Discovery's astronauts swung open  
the hatches of the international space station tonight and floated 
into the chilly but brightly lit outpost. They were the first 
visitors in six months. Before the seven shuttle astronauts began 
opening the doors, flight controllers warned it would be 57 degrees 
in the first module, the American-made Unity. The astronauts will 
spend the next three days making repairs and deliveries to the 
240-mile-high station, vacant since December. It's bigger and far 
more tedious work than what they did earlier today during the 
second-longest spacewalk ever -- rigging cranes and other tools to 
the exterior. 

</P>
<P>
	Hostages Released in Columbia  
</P>
<P>
	CALI, Colombia (AP) -- About 100 churchgoers were kidnapped by  
Leftist Colombian rebels today, but about at least 79 have been 
released. The rebels captured took the people from a Mass in an 
exclusive neighborhood and drove them into the countryside in 
trucks. The rebels belonged to the National Liberation Army, 
authorities said. However, there was no claim of responsibility. At 
least two guerrillas were killed and one rebel and two soldiers 
wounded in firefights, said an army commander said. 

</P>
<P>
	Energy Dept. Firings Expected  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said today he  
would fire department officials for failing to act on signs China 
was stealing secrets from a U.S. nuclear weapons lab. Dismissals 
and demotions could come as early as this week, after Richardson 
receives an internal report on security lapses at the Los Alamos 
lab in New Mexico that may have contributed to China's thefts of 
U.S. nuclear secrets. Richardson said China got information on 
three nuclear warheads but there is no evidence China has used that 
information to modernize or deploy nuclear weapons. 

</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu Confirms Talks With Syria  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Benjamin Netanyahu acknowledged conducting  
secret talks with Syria that came close to an agreement for 
substantial withdrawals from the Golan Heights, a Cabinet minister 
said today. Netanyahu, trounced by moderate Ehud Barak in elections 
two weeks ago, outwardly maintained an unwavering commitment to 
Israeli sovereignty over the strategic plateau, captured in the 
1967 Mideast war. 

</P>
<P>
	San Jose Chinatown Unearthed  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Archaeologists have unearthed evidence  
of a turn-of-the-century Chinatown. City records, newspaper 
accounts and fire insurance maps suggested the existence of a 
Chinese community, but no traces had been found until the 
excavations. The site was discovered as crews prepared for 
construction on a freeway extension. Excavations began in April but 
were kept secret to prevent looting. By Friday, the site was 
covered by dirt again after artifacts, including an oil lamp and 
glassware, were removed. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose moderately in early trading  
Monday. The Nikkei rose 50.08 points to 16,022.76 early. On Friday, 
the average shed 204.51 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Take First Game From Pacers  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Allan Houston led the New York Knicks with  
19 points en route to the team's 93-90 win over the Indiana Pacers. 
Reggie Miller had a chance to tie the game with 15 seconds left, 
but missed from his favorite 3-point spot. The win gives the Knicks 
Game 1 of the Eastern Conference finals. The Knicks also got 16 
points each from Patrick Ewing and Latrell Sprewell and 15 from 
Larry Johnson. 

</P>
<P>
	Rookie Beem Wins Kemper Open  
</P>
<P>
	POTOMAC, Md. (AP) -- Rookie Rich Beem, who battled an upset  
stomach hours before tee time, birdied three of the first five 
holes and cruised to his first PGA Tour victory today at the Kemper 
Open. Beem, who putted well all tournament, sank a 45-footer on the 
first hole, a 10-footer on the third and rattled one in from 25 on 
the fifth. By then he had a four-stroke lead, and he parred all but 
two holes the rest of the way for a 1-under-par round of 70 and a 
10-under 272 total, one shot ahead of Bradley Hughes and two-time 
champion Bill Glasson. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
