<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Moni Maker Upset in Swedish Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Moni Maker, the 1998 Horse of the Year  
and the world's fastest trotter, was upset in the Elitloppet on 
Sunday in a race won by Remington Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Remington Crown, a Swedish-bred horse from France, received a  
perfect tactical ride from Joseph Verbeeck in one of the most 
prestigious harness races. 
</P>
<P>
	Verbeeck's victory came less than two days after he was attacked  
by two bikers on the French Riviera while driving his convertible 
to his Monte Carlo home. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the second victory at Solvalla Racetrack for the French  
champion driver, who also won with Sea Cove in the 1993 Elitloppet. 
</P>
<P>
	Moni Maker, the defending champion, was the overwhelming  
favorite for the $420,000 race. But the 6-year-old mare, who gave 
American driver Wally Hennessey his first victory in this race last 
year, never made a serious charge on the final straightaway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had planned to take the lead and then slow down the pace a  
bit,'' Verbeeck said. ``Moni Maker was not in top form today. 
Remington Crown is one of the best. I like him a lot'' 
</P>
<P>
	Remington Crown covered the mile in 1:56.8. Moni Maker was  
second, a length behind. Canadian entry Goodtimes, driven by David 
Wall, finished third. 
</P>
<P>
	Remington Crown, sold to a French stable last year, also won the  
first of two qualifying heats held earlier Sunday and earned a 
total of $238,000. She now has 36 wins in 67 races. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the 18th victory for a French-owned entry in the  
Elitloppet. Sweden is second with 14 wins, followed by Italy (five) 
and the United States (four). 
</P>
<P>
	Verbeeck said he had no time to react when he was attacked  
outside Cannes. 
</P>
<P>
	``They hit me in the face with baseball bats. They were trying  
to steal my car,'' he said. ``I've read about similar incidents 
recently in France. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was lucky. A taxi cab came up to the traffic lights and the  
bikers fled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Verbeeck spent six hours at his dentist Saturday before flying  
to Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did a good job,'' he said. ``I don't look pretty now. But,  
of course, I've never been a handsome guy.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
