<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Ponders Senate Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- The president and first lady wrapped up a  
quiet Florida vacation Sunday in a way only the Clintons could -- 
sitting in on a conference about progressive politics. 
</P>
<P>
	The annual forum sponsored by a wing of the Democratic  
Leadership Council was held at White Oak Plantation, a sprawling 
wildlife preserve where President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, 
have been relaxing since Tuesday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides to the first lady suggested that in between eying the  
giraffes, white rhinoceroses and other species at the plantation, 
she was pondering her potential bid for the Senate from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	While flying back to Washington Sunday night, the president was  
asked by reporters if Mrs. Clinton had decided whether to run. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever she's for, I'm for,'' he answered. ``I gave her  
probably what I gave everybody. You have to know, you need to know 
why you want the job. You have to be able to tell somebody in 30 
seconds. You have to be able to tell somebody in five minutes. You 
have to be able to give a 30-minute talk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether the Clintons would vacation in New York state this  
summer, he replied, ``I'll go wherever she wants to go, from now 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prominent players in Democratic politics, as well as like-minded  
politicos from abroad, attended the plantation conference, which 
was closed to the press. Mrs. Clinton offered no hint at a morning 
meeting whether she had come to a decision, according to one 
attendee. 
</P>
<P>
	But a longtime adviser to the first lady said that the longer  
she waits to make an official move, the more likely it was that she 
would run. Otherwise, other potential Democratic candidates would 
be cheated of time. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Mrs. Clinton comes back in very early June and doesn't say  
`no,' I think it's fair to assume that she's going to move 
forward,'' the adviser said, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The next step would be the formation of an exploratory committee  
in July to cover the costs of unofficial campaigning in New York. A 
bid for the seat in 2000 likely will cost $15 million or more. 
</P>
<P>
	James Carville, who managed President Clinton's 1992 campaign,  
said on CNN's ``Late Edition'' Sunday that he expected that she 
would decide to run. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything I know and conversations I've had with any number  
of people, the first lady included, indicates to me that this is 
something that she really wants to do,'' Carville said. ``I expect 
her to mount a heck of an effective campaign.... And I expect her 
to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One concern has been how the first lady would handle the  
increased scrutiny she would come under once she was the candidate, 
and not just the candidate's wife. 
</P>
<P>
	But in an interview published Sunday in The New York Times  
Magazine she said that she was prepared for such scrutiny after the 
attacks she and her family have weathered from the Whitewater 
investigation through the Monica Lewinsky scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has crossed my mind. But the possibility of partisan or  
political attacks does not serve as a deterrent,'' she said. ``That 
is not anything that would prevent me, after having been through 
what we've been through, from deciding to run for office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The subject of the fifth annual ``working retreat'' at White Oak  
was ``The Politics of the Third Way'' -- the term moderate Democrats 
have coined for Clinton's blend of restrained economic policies and 
liberal social agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton gave an 11 a.m. address to the group. She and the  
president were mingling with the guests after a roundtable in the 
late afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Also attending the forum were Mark Penn, the president's  
pollster; Bruce Reed, the White House domestic policy adviser; DLC 
head Al From; Rep. Cal Dooley, D-Calif.; David Milband, an adviser 
to British Prime Minister Tony Blair; and Tony Giddens, director of 
the London School of Economics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
