<DOCNO> APW19990530.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 17:02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Victims Still Coping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. (AP) -- An American flag flies at half-staff  
on what is left of Suzanne Cox's home this Memorial Day weekend. 
The flag hovers over a waist-high pile of rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	The stars and stripes pay tribute to Ms. Cox. The 55-year-old  
was the first to be fatally injured in the deadly Oklahoma 
tornadoes a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	It was at her home that a tornado at least a half-mile wide  
touched down and continued on a deadly path that killed 43 others 
across the state May 3. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 800 people were injured and 8,093 homes were damaged  
or destroyed. Insured losses total at least $955 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The tornado's trail is still visible looking north from Ms.  
Cox's home. The few patches of green are new. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new grass and leaves on the trees helps,'' said Bridge  
Creek Superintendent Terry Brown. ``It helps cover up the wounds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A month later, the streets have been opened and the curfews have  
ended. But this is the phase that some say is the hardest. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the crying stage,'' said Kay Norman, the Bridge Creek  
elementary principal. 
</P>
<P>
	The high school's cafeteria, which served as a morgue after the  
storms, now is home to the Small Business Administration, the 
Federal Emergency Management Agency and various insurance agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims must deal with the officials and watch for the  
unofficial. Reported cases of fraud included contractors being paid 
by homeowners to remove debris from private property that was 
covered by government aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Little League baseball has begun in Bridge Creek. It was this  
rural community southwest of Oklahoma City that suffered the 
highest deaths per capita in the storms. Twelve people died in the 
community of 8,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Paulmore threw baseballs this weekend to his 15-year-old  
and 12-year-old sons behind Bridge Creek High School. Paulmore, a 
firefighter, is an assistant coach for the Firehawks, the Little 
League team. 
</P>
<P>
	He was part of the initial search teams for the living and then  
helped recover the dead that Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still hard. Some of those people who died I had breakfast  
with the day before,'' Paulmore said. ``We all know everyone around 
here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
