<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 06:18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Swede Wins European Song Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- A Swedish singer won Europe's biggest song  
contest on Sunday in Jerusalem with a performance that was a 
throwback to the 1970s and the Swedish supergroup ABBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlotte Nilsson, who won by singing ``Take Me To Your Heaven''  
in a 1970s-style pink-and-beige pantsuit, acknowledged the song 
mimicked the harmonies and chorus of the Swedish band. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess it sounds a little like ABBA,'' she said at a news  
conference after the contest. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyricist Gert Lengstrand, who wrote the winning song along with  
Lars ``Dille'' Didricson, grabbed the microphone and quickly jumped 
to Nilsson's defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing wrong with sounding like the most popular  
group in the world,'' he said. ABBA was propelled to international 
fame after winning the Eurovision song contest in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	Countries participating in the contest conducted telephone polls  
in the five minutes after the contest ended at midnight Saturday. 
Respondents may not vote for their own country. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout much of the contest, Sweden was neck-and-neck with  
Iceland's Selma, who sang an upbeat techno-influenced song, ``All 
Out of Luck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Sweden's fourth win. Abba's 1974 winner, ``Waterloo,''  
provoked controversy because the band performed the song in 
English. 
</P>
<P>
	That led to a rule limiting entries to languages that are widely  
spoken in the competitor's homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the rule was lifted for the first time since 1975 and  
led to much discussion of national identity during the rehearsals 
the week before the contest. About half of the 23 entries were in 
English, the Bosnian entry was in French, and the German entry was 
in Turkish. 
</P>
<P>
	Nilsson said she believed singing lyrics in English helped her  
win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure I would have won if I had sung in Swedish,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultra-Orthodox Jews had threatened to disrupt the festival,  
partly because it involved dress rehearsals on the Sabbath and 
partly because it featured a return performance by Dana 
International, the transsexual who won the title for Israel last 
year in Britain singing ``Diva.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Contest organizers rescheduled rehearsals to appease the  
Sabbath-observant, but International still performed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
