<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Actor Billy Barty Injured in Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GARDEN GROVE, Calif. (AP) -- Billy Barty, the diminutive actor  
whose career spans seven decades, was injured when a scooter he was 
riding flipped over and dropped him headfirst onto a concrete set 
of stairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Barty, 74, was leaving an outdoor stage after performing at the  
Garden Grove Strawberry Festival when the accident happened Friday. 
His face was bruised and he suffered a fractured eye socket in the 
fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel good. I just look horrible,'' Barty said Sunday from  
his home. 
</P>
<P>
	Barty has used the motorized scooter since undergoing hip  
surgery about a month ago. The scooter apparently lost a wheel. 
Barty said he was leaving the stage ``and the next thing I knew I 
was in the ambulance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-foot-10 Barty appeared in his first Hollywood feature in  
1927 at age 3. He has played a number of outrageous characters in 
his career. Just a few of his roles include a wizard in the movie 
``Willow,'' a tongue-in-cheek stint as a German spy in ``Under the 
Rainbow'' with Chevy Chase and a suspected stalker in ``Foul 
Play.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990530.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 09:11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colleges Offer Vietnam War Courses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- They liked Jim Blight's impression of  
Lyndon Johnson. They liked how his face drooped like a basset 
hound's, how he would adopt a Texas drawl to praise the ``brave 
boys'' in ``Vee-yet Nam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	None of these Brown University students was alive during  
America's misadventure in Vietnam, yet like many others of their 
generation they wanted to know so much about it. 
</P>
<P>
	So Blight, their professor, pulled out all the stops. He did his  
LBJ impersonation -- not bad for a skinny guy from Flint, Mich. He 
described his own part in the peace movement. 
</P>
<P>
	And for the spring semester's last session, he introduced Robert  
S. McNamara, an architect of the war. For the moment, the '60s came 
alive. 
</P>
<P>
	When the former defense secretary acknowledged he had harbored  
doubts that the war could be won, one student argued that McNamara 
should have gone public right away with his qualms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had you spoken frankly, it seems years of war could have been  
avoided,'' said Michael Ellsberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellsberg was a flower-power baby. His father is Daniel Ellsberg,  
the man who leaked the Pentagon Papers, and a one-time member of 
the McNamara team who came to oppose the war. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Ellsberg is 22. He remembers his father telling him  
``very subtle points'' about U.S. war policy that he couldn't 
really grasp because he was too young. Now, he says, he has an avid 
interest in the war and in his father's role: ``I have a unique 
resource right in my own home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His classmate Jeffrey Dillon's father, on the other hand, has  
told him little about his time in Vietnam as a U.S. Marine 
machine-gunner at a base at Da Nang. He knows that his father still 
believes the United States could have won if it had used greater 
military force. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace activists ``would talk about peace and love, and then  
treat people who disagreed with them with contempt. That's 
hypocritical,'' says the senior from Brick, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	But he wanted to know more. And he's not alone among the sons  
and daughters of the people who fought the war and fought over the 
war. Though Vietnam is a conflict many Americans would sooner 
forget, it is relived year-round in classrooms throughout the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Just ask Blight and colleagues like Robert Brigham, a history  
professor at Vassar College in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., who also teaches 
about the war. ``These courses are among the most popular on 
American campuses,'' says Brigham. 
</P>
<P>
	Their parents fought, protested, fled to Canada, savored high  
draft numbers, tuned in, turned on, dropped out. Today's students 
envy their parents for having lived through the era, and they are 
fascinated by everything about it: the music, the politics, the 
sense of cause. 
</P>
<P>
	``This generation sees their parents' generation as the  
measuring stick,'' says Brigham. ``They feel that that time period 
is hanging over everything they do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Levy's dad opened up about his Vietnam-era history  
when she coaxed him. He had long hair back in those days, and he 
recalls trying to sleep in his frat house while someone played 
``In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida'' on a stereo. He was, she says, probably less 
of a hippie than he looked. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Levy, 20, from Orono, Maine, overheard her parents talk  
about her father's fear of being drafted when his college deferment 
expired upon graduation. His luck held, and he was never called to 
fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Quang Do's father also escaped the war.  
</P>
<P>
	He moved from South Vietnam to California in 1968 to study  
engineering and joined a group of other South Vietnamese students 
who protested the war. It was up to the Vietnamese to choose their 
destiny, he believed, without interference from the United States 
or any other country. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans have a one-sided view of the war -- obsessed with the  
58,000 soldiers they lost without giving much thought to the 3.8 
million Vietnamese who died, laments Quang, 21, of Rancho Palos 
Verdes, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	A fan of the Beatles' ``Abbey Road'' and ``White Album,'' Quang  
is certain that he would have joined the antiwar movement had he 
been in his father's shoes: ``There's no doubt in my mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jennifer Thompson knows of no one in her family who fought in  
the war or protested it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew very little about the war. I knew there was a movement  
against the war in the '60s,'' says the 22-year-old from New 
Rochelle, N.Y.,'' but I didn't know why, other than the movement 
said it was immoral and unjust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson admires the 1960s because it was ``a time of activism,  
when people actually cared about issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole idea of being involved, of not being afraid to take  
the least-traveled road'' is something that appeals to her. 
</P>
<P>
	That road was taken by her professor, Blight. He joined the  
1960s peace movement as a student at the University of Michigan. In 
1970, he was among marchers who carried a giant black coffin to the 
Ann Arbor post office to protest the fatal shooting of four 
students by the National Guard during an antiwar demonstration at 
Kent State University. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Blight's students signed up for his Vietnam seminar  
because they'd heard he is a lively lecturer. He doesn't 
disappoint. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to get weepy. But a lot happens in 1968,'' he  
said. He told them about communist guerrillas on suicide attacks 
during the Tet Offensive, and about the assassination of Bobby 
Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Blight talked about Johnson's struggles to deal with mounting  
opposition to the war, and about LBJ's credibility problem among 
the ruling elite: ``He sounded like a hillbilly. He looked like a 
hillbilly. Lyndon Johnson was no Jack Kennedy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When his students ask him about his peacenik past, he is bemused  
by their fascination with the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jimi Hendrix once draped the American flag around himself.  
What can that possibly mean to this generation?'' asks Blight, a 
professor of international relations. 
</P>
<P>
	And yet, the relevance of Vietnam hit home to some students when  
McNamara lectured. He told the class that some of the same mistakes 
made by the United States during the Vietnam War are being repeated 
in NATO's war with Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see the pattern set in Vietnam,'' worries Elizabeth Levy.  
</P>
<P>
	The trauma of Vietnam lasts beyond final exams.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
